I have been with PayPal since 2007, I buy and sell on EBay, and also use PayPal for personal and business use outside of PayPal. I sold an item on EBay but the buyer was having issues logging into PayPal through EBay so they sent me the money through PayPal Goods & Services. It‚Äôs been 2 days and my money is still being held, item has already shipped and I added the tracking number to the PayPal transaction. When I call I am told it is the automatic security protocol and it is not anything that can be corrected by a person. I asked how long the hold is, I was told ‚ÄúOh, we‚Äôre not told that, this way if a scammer calls trying to steal money, we can‚Äôt tell them when to try and transfer the money again. The hold is for as long as the security system wants it to be and that‚Äôs solely controlled by the computer system.‚Äù Seriously? A computer, who does not have a mortgage, a family, bills, or a life, is in sole control of when I can have my money. The sale was for over $1,000 and I even added money to the account at the recommendation of a PayPal associate to ‚Äútrick the system, since you‚Äôre adding money from the account you‚Äôre trying to transfer to so you can‚Äôt possibly be stealing.‚Äù Now that money is stuck in ‚Äúcomputer-controlled hold‚Äù also. Customer Service has been rude, unhelpful, and unknowledgeable. I can believe the lack of competency and that no one can do anything to get me my money. I mean they had me create a second account and try to transfer it there and then literally said ‚Äúwell, beats me!‚Äù when it did not work. Very frustrating, just lost a loyal long-time customer and her long-time customer parents, family, and friends.

What‚Äôs the Blazes happened to my review!?  (to ‚ÄúSifu_Char‚Äù: You CAN use VLCr on more than one iPhone, as long as all devices are connected to the same local area network. You can even use VLC Remote on two iPhones and one Android if you have it installed on there as well. The set up for VLC Remote only needs to be run once, after that you can connect as many devices to VLC as you have devices that have VLC remote installed on, and they don‚Äôt all have to be iPhones, The android app detects VLC after it has been set up just like the iPhone version. Hope that helps.)  I am afraid this app has fallen into disuse over the last couple of years, mostly due to many people moving to an easier platform to maintain: namely PLEX and PLEX pass.  But back when iPhones were a new deal, people mostly used one app and one app only to maintain their private video library‚Äôs: and that would be VLC aka VideoLAN. Video LAN as in Local Area Network, where we could network several home computers, share all of the media libraries, create multitudes of playlists and then have ongoing movie play back for days and days and years even.  And wouldn‚Äôt such an app require a remote control for us couch potato types? Enter VLC Remote.  Now we could have access to every of the cool features of VLC, change aspect ratio, language, alternate streams, we could play back DVDs, Blu-ray‚Äôs, MKV, FLV, AVI, WMV, MP4, MOV, and many other obscure formats that (OGG) all play back beautifully from one app.  I had the privilege of beta testing this app for a couple of years and a lot of the cool features in this app I remember discussing, in fact the way that it is now is the direct result of a core group of us who used to bounce ideas back-and-forth between us and the developer. Who is a great guy and he even put out a ‚ÄúVLC remote classic‚Äù for me and one other person and I still have that installed in one of my devices.   There was even a ‚Äúheadset mode‚Äú, an EXPERIMENTAL FEATURE with skull and cross bones warning, which works actually pretty well except that you have to manually sync up the audio on the hand devices to what‚Äôs playing on the TV, but it does give you a way of having a headset on from 20 feet away and you don‚Äôt have to have a 50 foot headphone cable (üòÇ). Is headset mode still there? YES! I was just using it.  These days most of the cool things that we were able to do with VLC we can now do with Plex media server, and so I feel badly that from my perspective this app has fallen along on the wayside to the point where my iOS 11 App Store automatically offloads the app on occasion ‚òπÔ∏è.  But whenever I do finally fire up VLC on my home network, I still use this app to manipulate it rather than having to get off my rear end, drag my butt over to the computer and mess with the interface there, in fact the combination of VLC Remote and Mobile Mouse gives me the ability to fire up VLC from Mobile Mouse üêÅ üê≠ and then I can move to VLC remote to access the app.  Lately the developer has been creating something called the ChillRemote which actually can give you a Remote for things like Netflix and Amazon and YouTube and it works pretty well, my only complaint with that is that it has a subscription feature to give you access to more features of the app and I loathe and despise subscription features. Mostly because that most developers that instigate a subscription use it to immediately bilk their former users out of a lot more money than the paid features usually cost in a one time payment. Rob does not do that though. He doesn‚Äôt ask very much for the subscription for ChillRemote, but I hate the concept of subscriptions, especially if it includes removal of advertisements which used to be a $.99 in app purchase for most apps. I have been using this app for 8 years and it always had my back. Every teacher, assignment, and class imputes and used for 13 distinct semesters. My biggest fear was the app would stop being updated but the team at iStudiez instead always strived to add more features and make the app better. I have belatedly updated my USOpen.org 2019 app and found it (as of 9/7/2019) to be improved but still far from impressive in its design or its journalism.  Previously, I could not find match statistics that worked, or live radio. Both are fine now.   A new tab at the bottom of the screen leads to ‚ÄúPlayers.‚Äù Thank you. But why does it have only individual statistics, not individual bios? If you can‚Äôt write them, please at least link to Wikipedia.  Match previews are written cheerfully but inelegantly. They include outright typos like ‚ÄúRoger‚Äù Cup for ‚ÄúRogers‚Äù and inexcusable coding in the middle of sentences, as in the following two paragraphs:  Serena: "I've felt more prepared this tournament...?external=true I just feel like I've actually had time to train."  Patrick Mouratoglou: "...I?external=true think her movement now is better than I have ever seen since she became a mother."  Apparently, these embarrassments were caused by ellipses, which should not be used anyway in feature interviews though they may be needed when quoting legal documents. The assumption is, readers understand that all quotes from oral interviews are excerpted. We KNOW Patrick said other things before (and after) this quote!  Slide shows of still photos are excellent technically and artistically but next to worthless journalistically because they lack captions describing the significance, if any, of the moment shown. Instead, a boilerplate caption is used on almost every caption: ‚ÄúSo-and-so in action against so-and-so in the nth round,‚Äù etc. Your images obviously are selected for their design value, not their significance, which is nice, but we‚Äôve all seen thousands and thousands of beautiful tennis stills. Video clips with interpretation on the soundtrack would be far more interesting, even for users who don‚Äôt play tennis.  Like the post-match stories, the photos emphasize the positive, becoming more like PR than journalism. That means this app cannot become a fan‚Äôs go-to place for all things US Open. Moreover, the mainstream media complete their postgame reports many minutes earlier than this app.   Maybe just give up on the journalism and become more like the website of a state legislature: schedules, outcomes and repositories of history. In addition, US Open could curate and amalgamate others‚Äô journalism, as Apple News does.

Good game if you play with other humans.  Representative of the real article. Only drawbacks are:  1) Symbols are a bit hard to see/interpret on a smaller screen (phone) but not an issue on a tablet.   *2) The rampant use of ‚Äúcomputer cheating‚Äù if you are playing solo. Anytime you‚Äôre a victory point ahead of the others, numerous 7s will be rolled, Knight cards will be played, and no one will trade cards with you. The robber never moves anywhere but your spaces regardless of other considerations. Absurdity isn‚Äôt even close to an accurate word.

Overall, this is a good rendition of the board game Catan. The board game rules are adhered to (except that the computer decides without rolling the dice who puts down their first settlement), and the dice rolls are mostly fair and realistic (though in one game, the robber was rolled about a third of the time and no 8s were ever rolled). I‚Äôve heard from other reviews that the dice tries to help the AI when you‚Äôre close to winning, and this is probably true to some extent, but I was still able to win a lot of the time. It‚Äôs also great how the different characters in the game have their own personalities and levels of skill, so you‚Äôre not playing against the same AI each time.   There is a problem with the distribution of development cards in the game. Once, I was in the lead by 3 points and one of the AIs somehow won by acquiring 5 victory-point cards in a row, even though there are supposed to be 5 one-victory-point cards in the game set and 25 development cards in total. It‚Äôs also very difficult to see what the AIs are trading, whether with each other or the bank. In general, the AIs seem to rely more on development cards than most real-life Catan players and often don‚Äôt build settlements when they could very likely be able to do so.  Otherwise, I would recommend buying this app if you rarely get to play the physical Catan board game.

I got this app to help teach my son his lowercase letters (already knew uppercase) in a fun way. I love how customizable the app is! In a short time my son has learned many of these words.

In settings there is an option to make the user spell from left to right. Everytime you select a letter, the app says it and then will spell the word and pronounce it. My three year is definitely engaged and will repeat the letters along with the app!

4 thumbs UP!  (2 from me, 2 from the kid)  Our 3.5-year-old will easily sit half an hour playing this game (he would keep going if I'd let him).  I like its simplicity without extra fluff.  All the  setup options are very intuitive and straight forward too.  Our son kept picking letters out of order, and it was bugging the OCD in me.  So I went to settings, and there it was, the "left to right" option.  Tada!  We've only played the shapes category so far, but I like the variety that goes beyond the regular, way too common geometric shapes.   Having the Japanese option was actually the determining factor for us, and I would think any parents who are raising their children in one of the optional languages would really appreciate the multi-lingual function.   We had the free version for a long time but now that our son is really picking up on letters and sounds, we decided to get the full version even though I knew the app was old with no updates of late. But lo and behold, I was pleased to see that it was just updated a month ago! Yay!   The animation and the drawings are very basic, which can be improved, I suppose. I do however like the bold (again, simple in a good way) colors.

I‚Äôve been searching for weeks to find a decent app to help me design logos for me and my friends YouTube channels and instagram and nothing has come close to being as easy to use as this while at the same time giving you the power to create something that‚Äôs all your own. Was especially excited when I went to draw freehand and the app corrected my crappy little squiggles and made them smooth lines, (with option to turn that function off) very user friendly for brand new artist with terrible penmanship!üòÇ

And it keeps getting better!  I‚Äôve been using this app for years (under a different app name for a while) and I continue to easily turn out nice drawings that are more than adequate. Best of all, using the features does not force me into deep memory recall or searching for the feature I need after every update.  When I have had an issue it was always my fault, but later a new version would make the correct way to do it obvious.  For example, I always had a problem understanding the set operations like Union.  Not with the latest version‚Äîthey simply work obviously.  Now I wonder why I was ever confused.  The only other issue I‚Äôve had has been the shape libraries.  There isn‚Äôt really any problem with what is provided, I just want more‚Äîlike network device shapes.  I create my own, of course, but I never seemed to be able to find one that I needed. Somehow this was fixed.  I just created shapes for casters (fixed, rotating, locking) and there they are just where I need them when I want them.  It wasn‚Äôt automagic, it just worked like my brain though it should.  And that is why this program is great.  Unlike other drawing Apps, Graphic works they way I think it is supposed to so I don‚Äôt have to learn and remember vast minutiae of app oddities.  I already have to much of that rolling around‚Äîlike a pin-ball machine in my brain where there are rarely extra points for collisions.  So why can‚Äôt we have in-app purchases of shape libraries please, or a set of design rules and a website to share the things?  Not that I am complaining.  I have gotten every design drawing completed that I ever wanted, and without calling my friendly drafting expert!  And in jig time.  Thanks.

Although I enjoy the content of Wired magazine, I would NOT recommend subscribing digitally through this app.  Once you subscribe, you will receive an incessant stream of spam from Cond√© Nast that will continue despite all your attempts to unsubscribe and mark as junk mail. Since moving to the iPad several years ago as my primary reading device, there are certain standards that I have come to expect with my digital publications.   The number one requirement is that the content supports both portrait and landscape modes, not just portrait mode, as WIRED still only does. I and most people I encounter who use an iPad use some form of case and/or keyboard cover that puts the device into landscape mode for TIME magazine used to offer both modes, but then they went portrait-only and I found it totally frustrating and dropped the subscription.  There are several other digital publications that don‚Äôt suffer from this problem (I‚Äôve used the ZINIO reader for a few things), so this is not a difficult problem to solve.  Other reviewers have commented on the lack of zoom and other viewing controls and I agree with their concerns.  Finally, the new ‚ÄúSwipe down‚Äù control isn‚Äôt as easy as the prior control.  If you‚Äôre not careful, you‚Äôll swipe down from the top and reveal an iPad control, not the WIRED app control to get back to the menu and settings.  This is not as intuitive and it doesn‚Äôt work as well.  I‚Äôd just assume see the older control where you tapped on the content to reveal the menu bar at the top.  Please listen to your customers while you have them and make these changes.  These are much more fundamental things and make more of a difference than animated cover pages and other bells and whistles.

This is my first ever App Store review, and its for this app. This app is my go to navigation app, along with google maps. I‚Äôve tried tens of other apps, and none beats the value or functionality this app. For a one time $4 fee, I‚Äôve got everything.   Features I found really useful/invaluable- 1- offline nav. There are other apps that also offers this, but the value isn‚Äôt there. They either ask for a subscription, or their maps aren‚Äôt as detailed or as useful. 2- choice of maps. In the states I like usgs topo, or topo map 1 or 2. Elsewhere, topo map 1 seems to be my go to- it has a lot of bike lanes mapped out around urban areas, and the terrain features are succinct. 3- route building. There are a few routing services (mapquest, graphhopper, yours) that you can play around with, and generally they are on point. They have a good balance between directness, best route for your method of going (biking, car, hiking, etc), and common sense (not trying to go above be the highest mountain even if it‚Äôs the most direct) 4- search. Search feature/point of interests surprisingly will show up even the most obscure place in remote areas 5- various app settings. All super useful - you can manually reduce gps accuracy, change overlay settings to make things easier to read, all super useful when I‚Äôm looking for a no frills app that will make efficient use of my precious iPhone battery. Other apps look and seem clunky that will take up tons of battery, all for a nice shiny look, but with crap functionality 6- recording. You can record and export your gpx file, super useful for journaling and keeping track.   All in all, I keep coming back to this app. Other apps seem seductive, but this app does it all and it does it with no fuss, all bang. You guys rock!

I have been using this app for about two years now, and it has proven itself useful time and time again. The GPS is surprisingly accurate, and the terrain models show a sufficient amount of detail. The ability to save offline chunks and plot and track routes is what makes this app awesome. It has saved me many times when the trail disappears under snow or I decide to take a ‚Äòshortcut‚Äô or excursion and lose the trail. It helped me through a 5-day trip in the Sierra range, as well as more day hikes than I can count. It also has proved useful for plotting overland 4x4 trips. Can definitely recommend. Only problem is the step-up structured payment system... it would be nice to just have one Pro version that gives full access to whatever the app can offer.  tl;dr: This app is accurate, helpful, and awesome. Only drawback is the payment structure. Recommend for any outdoor enthusiast.

Update 5/13:  While I appreciate the three or so updates over the past month (having gone without any updates for more than 3 years), the artificial intelligence (or "computer") opponent, when playing on the hardest setting, is permitted an unlimited number of back-and-forth moves in the same two spaces; whereas than the human player is afforded apx. two. This latest iteration of Fruit Ninja is a complete shadow of its former self in my opinion. It's one that is totally corrupted by micro-transactions by all accounts.  When I first bought Fruit Ninja on my Android devices and then now Apple devices, forever ago, the game was brilliant in my opinion. But, over the years this once great title has just gotten worse and worse with the inclusion of myriad in-app purchases, advertisements and ultimately - developer greed.  I think it would be so cool if, Halfbrick, offered a classic version of Fruit Ninja as a one time purchase, with no vile advertisements for other Halfbrick games or otherwise and absolutely no in-app purchases. Sadly, because of the aforementioned greed I just really don't see that lovely idea ever happening.   You'd think that after all the money this developer has made from Fruit Ninja and its other titles, that they would be cool enough to offer a classic version of this game. Like I said, though, I don't ever see that happening with Halfbrick truly being lost to greed.  That fact is very unfortunate in my opinion because this used to be one of the best video games available on mobile devices and elsewhere I always thought. Heck, I even bought a copy of Fruit Ninja for my Xbox 360 back in the day to play it using Kinect. And let me tell you, that was an awesome way to play this game, using your arms like swords to slash fruit and rack up crazy combos. I found as well that it was a really good physical workout.   So, I have no aversion to spending my hard earned money on quality video games offered by ethical and moral developers/studios. But Fruit Ninja and Halfbrick are so far removed from being ethical and moral now. That, honestly,  I refuse to spend even the lint in my pocket on the corrupted trash this once great title has truly become.

This is still a great supports them all photo and video sync application. Supports most major services, some computer protocols, hardware devices and cameras.  The UI is a bit of a mess, selection can involve many taps, thumbnails are small and not resizable, configuration options are daunting. Try their support web pages for documentation. Once you get set up transfer can be simple and painless, easily backing up your photos to multiple destinations with many options for filing and renaming. Geolocation triggers can be helpful and Siri automation can make kicking off a sync simple.  If you need a powerful photo and video sync app, you aren‚Äôt going to find any better than this.  My recommendations: a UI overhaul, and syncing settings and/or destinations between devices.

Just completed the game and honestly was unimpressed. Generally, I love adventure games, especially ones with a wink and a nod to their own campy mechanics. This one is overblown in its self-references and unnecessarily pared down to having a single pixel as a face. Like, it took half the game to realize the protagonist uses female gender pronouns. It has style, but seemingly for style's sake. The paper-thin plot is left like a series of archetypal placeholders, Jungian references without fleshed out characters, and yet, there seems to be one character that shines through: the unambitious, possibly stoner college guy voice that took some basic 101 courses on literature and psychology and thinks it sounds pretty rad to work big words into a video game without knowing why or what they mean. Still, walking around a cosmic grotto for a gameplay is ok with me. Kudos for a game about nothing. That's the one thing I actually liked.

Boy was I excited to see Deathsmiles return. I love this game, I love the smartphone mode with upgrade equipment, and bullet hell games just feel right to me with the immediacy of a touch interface with no lag.  I missed this game a lot when it woulf no longer run on current OS versions, so I was ecstatic to see it revived from the dead.   Sadly, there is one massive issue for longtime players and several really annoying UI issues on an iPhone X.  The biggest problem by far is that, upon opening, I got an error message in Japanese that the save file is corrupt... and had ALL my smartphone mode goodies vanish. Given that I had spent many, many hours grinding literally all but a single item, this was frustrating to put it mildly. At least my purchased items restored correctly.  The remaining annoyances:  - On an iPhone X the curtain graphic extrnds all the way to the edges of the screen, but the touch area does not. This is s disaster, since it means you still need to keep your finger on top of the gameplay to control, and if you drift too far your character just stops moving.  - Likewise on the right side, the buttons aren‚Äôt in the extended screen, instead blocking the gameplay area for no reason.  - It doesn‚Äôt hide the swipe bar on an iPhone X so if you don‚Äôt use the Accessibility trick for licking yourself in the app or shrink the gameplay area needlessly, you will keep bumping it when trying to hit buttons.   - You can‚Äôt rotate the screen. This is notably annoying because in the orientation they chose my left hand is on top of the bottom side speaker so I lose the left channel of audio. Flipping the screen like 99% of landscape apps allow would fix this.   - Button targets at the bottom of the screen are wonky, so it is difficult to tap some shop buttons and almost impossible to get the shop previews to display.  - The word ‚Äúlong‚Äù in any cutscene text is replaced with ‚ÄúInt32‚Äù, which is possibly the most hilarious find-and-replace error ever.  On the positive side, this new version fixes text clipping errors in the shop, and you can full screen it and move the screen to the left or right as well.  C‚Äômon, Cave, at least fix the UI bugs. The save loss bug makes me afraid it‚Äôll happen again if I spend hours grinding rare items.

This app is so basic, as it has preset configurations that simply ask you to drag and drop the circuit element into the empty spot. There is NO ability to create circuits nor make measurements of voltage, current, or resistance. It does have some nice descriptions, and allows the user to make the connection between the real-world objects and the circuit diagram on the board, however this is suitable for elementary school kids. I am a high school physics teacher and was hoping for MUCH more functionality, and if this is what you are also looking for, save your $1!

"Don't do THAT! You'll create a short circuit!"  Words you won't have to say if your kid(s) use this app (and it's sister app, Serial Circuits).  My son is actually learning quite a bit blithely blowing up the virtual batteries - and figuring out how you have to connect them to blow up 4 at the same time, instead of just a paltry 2.  The tutorials that accompany the lessons (and the mistakes) are pretty clear.   If you are looking for a puzzle game - this ain't it.  But if you are looking for an introduction to circuits and electricity, then you have a winner.  No parts to lose, simple pick-up and the melted wires are self repairing.   My very paltry complaints: i wish the lightbulbs would grow brighter and dimmer to reflect different power levels, and the interface is a bit repetitive and rigid.

You can also view static images of the animations by moving your finger left and right across the image. It‚Äôs a lot easier to learn to tie knots using this app than it is using Ashley‚Äôs Book of Knots.  I have recommended it to my friends, family and anyone who expresses an interest in knot-tying.

This game has great graphics and I love the tone.  The puzzles were interesting and generally well done.  There are two main drawbacks for me.  First, I think the game is too short given it‚Äôs price.  Second, I think the hint system, which is crucial for a game like this, has a terrible flaw.  Generally I don‚Äôt care that you have to play a mini game to access the walkthrough.  The problem is that it shows you the walkthrough for the area you‚Äôre in, regardless of where you might be in the chain of puzzles.  So you might have access to 6 or 7 areas and not be sure where to go next.  You‚Äôll have to go to each area, play the mini game, and hope there‚Äôs something you can actually do there.  This also means that you will sometimes bypass the actual puzzle accidentally because the walkthrough for the area you‚Äôre in just has the final solution to another area‚Äôs puzzle.

Major Conservatory-trained composer who taught Finale for 20+ years is a convert to Notion.  I like the simplicity of it, but wish that the documentation was a bit better and that updates were given a bit more frequently.  I do use the handwriting features, but find certain gestures to be enigmatic to the recognition engine.  One big suggestion I would give the developers would be to have a handwriting option that lets you notate an entire measure at a time and then click a button or move to the next measure before it‚Äôs interpreted.  I tend to write all my noteheads first, then the stems, then the beams, then the dots, and the engine starts recognizing what I‚Äôm writing too soon.  Also - a free-form handwritten staff would be VERY useful for jotting down notes and ideas without it being rendered into anything. Otherwise, it‚Äôs a great little tool to have with me wherever I go.

I was really enjoying this app, until I discovered that it lacked on of the most basic and necessary features - layers. Hi All,  This game is the greatest value out there. This is a great game and the originals make it even better.  Now, I know some people are going to gripe about the graphics in the bonus feature of the 1980s BT3.  What happened there is that the developers were porting the Apple 2 GS versions of the games (1 and 2) to the iPad.  There was no GS version of the Bards Tale 3, much to my disappointment back then. TL;DR: Zero stars - Plays sound even when you turn sounds and music off in settings - Still forces you to watch ads after every other turn even though this is a paid app.   Full Review:  There is a front on the home screen that constantly says ‚Äúribbit‚Äù every two seconds. I turned off both the sounds and music in the settings but the front still makes noise. What‚Äôs the point of turning off all sounds if the frog is still going to make noise? It‚Äôs super annoying as the frog keeps making noise every other second and no way to turn it off. Further, and even more annoying, is that the click sounds when you tap icons still plays even though I have sounds turned off and the games still make noise and sound effects such as the frogs saying ribbit.  This app is absolutely unplayable when in an environment where you need to be quiet.  I wanted to contact customer support or email feedback directly to the developers instead of leaving a poor review but there was no contact information on the app.  Hopefully this gets fixed. I‚Äôll be sure to update this review if I hear anything back or the issue gets a fix.  Another issue is the fact that this is a PAID app. It costs $1.99 yet there are still ads! What did I just pay $2.00 for? The whole reason people pay upfront for apps is so they don‚Äôt have to watch ads! I‚Äôm not paying money to sit and watch ads or to have to pay even more money to get rid of them. Completely defeats the purpose of purchasing a paid app. If I wanted to watch ads there are plenty of FREE apps on the App Store that allow me to do so. Paying most of the FREE apps with an in app purchase of a couple dollars or less gets rid of ads completely so why is your app $2.00 with ads? No thanks!!   I very highly DO NOT recommend this app unless they make it fair and stop playing ads for an app that we already have to pay for in the first place.

Since downloading this app I have used it daily for articulation therapy at my school.  Gone are the days of pulling out different decks of cards, sorting them into initial/medial/final positions and finding their match for all the different students I work with throughout my day; all I have to do is go to one compact device (my iPad) and use this app that has it all and more!   To have all sounds available in all positions of words at the word, carrier phrase, sentence, and reading levels helps manage my office of clutter and simplifies the work space for the students. I am hoping the developers will add the phonemic /r/ sounds (ar, air, ire, or, er) in all word positions to be targeted at the word, carrier phrase, sentence, and reading levels as well.  But, the app does allow the user to add your own pictures for target words individualized to the student(s) so I could create my own phonemic /r/ lists/pictures this way but for now I don‚Äôt have the time and I‚Äôll keep my fingers crossed they get to it first!    The app allows to easily create groups with each student focusing on their own sound(s) in various position(s) and level(s) to individualize each student‚Äôs needs to work on their own goals at their own pace.    One of my favorite features is the audio record and playback feature.  It has already proven effective with my students who typically have difficulty with self-monitoring skills.  My students are recognizing hearing themselves say the words incorrectly and are now self-monitoring their sounds better!    Lastly, not only does the app have articulation targets but they also have all of the phonological processes to target at the word level as well.  I am hoping levels for the carrier phrase and sentence levels for each to become available for students working through increasing the complexity of their speech while targeting phonological processes as well.

I have been a math geek since I was four years old (Eisenhower, the last great, or even good, Republican president was still in his first term) and I became an amateur topologist and horologist not long after. This app not only makes an extremely obtuse and non intuitive topic accessible, it also manages to make it enjoyable and...dare I say it: FUN !   I have shared this app with my nephews and nieces AND their children (some as young as 5 years old) and it has always elicited excitement, curiosity and many, many questions. It will be interesting to see how their very early exposure to easily accessible and yet extremely abstract concepts affects their abilities to process and assimilate abstract and obtuse ideas going forward (or, in this instance, rotating outward and folding up...).  I do, however, have one suggestion...although the two pages where you ‚Äòhack‚Äô the optic chiasma (meld two images into a ‚Äú3-D‚Äù facsimile) work fine on my iPhone and my iPad Mini they don‚Äôt do well on standard sized iPads. My arms, and I‚Äôm 6‚Äô4‚Äù tall, are too short to hold the screen far enough away to fix and hold the images in place while manipulating the conjoined image. If you were to make an iPad-friendly version of those two pages, one in which they are just a little bit closer together, it would vastly improve the experience.

Had been feeling totally out of control with food! For a few years now I‚Äôve been gaining weight and every week vowed that ‚Äúthis would be the day I start my diet.‚Äù Each time it was a failure and I kept saying tomorrow. Like an addict I had reached my bottom and was searching for anything that could help. I came across this app VGB and decided to give it a try. Almost immediately I noticed changes in my eating...smaller bites, really tasting my food and craving fruit!! This Is my 4th week and I‚Äôm down 15 lbs!!! I am a true believer. I love this program and how easy it‚Äôs been. If you want to lose weight or are feeling out of control with food please give this program a try!

I came across easyloss purely by accident, but after reading all of the reviews I could find...decided I had to dl it.  As someone who has been on pretty much every type of diet there is out there, this is a breath of fresh air because it ISNT a diet.  It gives you so much hope (and results!); you don't have to change your entire life to fit the confines of the latest fad diet...you just follow the guidelines.  The guidelines teach you to listen to your own body, and eat intuitively.  I honestly haven't changed what I'm eating at all, though I now don't have binge sessions, so I'm actually eating a lot less without any feelings of hunger or deprivation.  It's so simple, and yet our own  ability to eat intuitively has basically been programmed out of us!    The hypnosis sessions help to support your own resolve, and they really are great.  I've been able to lose 12lbs in 4 weeks...which is huge because usually I'll drop like 10lbs in 2 weeks on a proper "diet" and then fall off in some way (large or small) because I'm ravenous and cranky.  Because this isn't a diet, and you aren't restricting yourself, you don't get those feelings and it's so much easier to push on.  Instead of a big drop on the scale (water weight), my weight goes down a little bit on most days for a nice cumulative downward movement on the scale.  It's amazing!    I will say that when you read the guidelines you may think.."this is it?" ...well, yes, that IS it!  And then you'll realize as you continue eating, knowing the guidelines, just how much you've been overdoing it.  Eating just because it's x-o'clock and everyone else wants to eat, or eating a massive serving of food just because it's on your plate and then wanting to unbutton your pants or something crazy.  Try this, it works.  And it will give you your life back when it comes to food.  No more obsessive tracking or controlling the macro content of your meals, etc.  just eating how we were designed to eat...with these lovely folks helping you along the way with the hypnosis sessions and Facebook group.

Update 5: It is the worst when a great game is created by a terrible company. This game hasn't been updated in 8 months and is falling apart... server crashes, load times, ugh. Not to mention, it isn't a fair play game. Despite buying the game, it is dominated by those who pay more for turbo bikes. Im at a stall at level 4 because they often only do a single 4 star race per day and it is open bike meaning it gets dominated by paid for turbo bikes. They could easily add more 4-star bike specific races so it is talent, not money that wins...    Update 4: I really want to remove a star, but I will keep it at two because they did start releasing more ‚Äúkickass‚Äù bike parts which is the only way to upgrade from level 2 to 3. The reason for the update is Duel is now completely broken. Before it had issues matching with 1 out of 5 attempts working, which is still the problem, but now, when a race is finished, it doesn‚Äôt connect to server so just deletes the race... super frustrating especially because challenges are duels.  Update 3: I just upgraded from 1 star to 2 stars because they started adding more of the bike that upgrades level 2 bikes to level 3 bikes... after months of being stalled, I get to progress again üòÄ However, connectivity issues are seeming to get worse. Duel only matches ever 4th or 5th attempt and matchups tend to be very imbalanced. Also Tourneys often get server down issues... it seems the game is getting more popular, but their servers cant handle it.  Update 2: now tournaments is failing to record some of my times so I come in last. Either the game has developed serious bugs or <enter conspiracy theory here>. I did get a response from support who invited me to delete the game... are you kidding me?!? üò°  Update 1: now game has serious server issues with regular connection issues and duel matching just completely fell off. I will be happy when another company takes this concept and builds a better game. ‚Äî  Original: First off, this is an incredible game. Ive even built my own tracks online... here is the MAJOR problem that makes it soooo frustrating. First, I paid for the game, yet players can still spend more to get a bike that is unbeatable... learn from other games, let spending be vanity not performance... people lose interest after buying anyways because there is no more challenge. Next and probably the worst is you can get all first level bikes in a couple hours, second level bikes in a couple days, but 3rd level bike near impossible (been playing everyday for months) because they hold back the one bike needed to upgrade any level 2 bikes so all progress completely halts and all rewards in tourneys become useless... DONT PREVENT PROGRESS DUMB DUMBS, again monetize on vanity or secret unlocks, not performance or progress, you wreck the game. Finally, to make it even harder to unlock their rare-as-a-diamond-in-the-butt-crack-of-an-elephant bike is the fact that higher level bikes can compete in lower level races... this means the entire progress bar skews to the already haves instead of leveling the field... not very smart. I have written the devs regarding this issue but crickets...

This is a very comprehensive App and the learning curve is quite bumpy at the beginning because some of the features are not user friendly at all. You will have to devote some time to learn if you want to get the most of it.   This App has one major flaw, entering a new wine is a very complicated and time consuming thing. You cannot scan the wine front label nor the bar code like Vivino does. That leaves you with the only option to use the search option to find the wine that you want to add. The search icon to access the database to find your wine is on the top right and not in the main data entry area. When you start entering your wine most of the options that come up don‚Äôt have the correct harvest year of your wine specially if it is an international wine or if it is a recent harvest from 2016-2018. You have no other option to select the closest option and then change the year manually.   Furthermore you have to manually take picture of  the label of your wine bottles, because the database does not include a picture. The App allows you to enter up to 3 pictures but you have to take those pictures manually to each bottle during the adding wine process. The other day it took me almost an hour to enter into the App a full case of 12 bottles, after navigating to find the correct year of my wines and taking manual pictures of all my wines.   Adding the option of scanning the wine label or the bar code to quickly locate your wine like Vivino does is an absolute must. If they don‚Äôt do it the App is too much time consuming and will require a lot of time to perform the most basic thing which is adding a new wine.

It‚Äôs a great app overall, but I was very disappointed on the lack of information for the different Champagne sub regions. Also, wines like champagne don‚Äôt usually come from a single year, so it would be useful to have the option of introducing ranges, including a separate year for the d√©gorgement.
Not user friendly when putting wines into app. Difficult and time consuming.

As a professional Architect, I have used BlueBeam for years in the office and in the field.  I liked that I could easily get files onto my iPad through the Studio feature, and I liked the ability to create tool sets on the Desktop that would transfer to the iPad app.  However, ever since Nametshek bought BlueBeam, there seems to have been a complete lack of support and development for the iPad app.  Seriously: not even a release to fix bugs in at least 11 months!  Most good apps release bug fixes every week or two.  I also see all of the instability issues that the other reviewers mention.  Whenever another Architect asks me how I use BlueBeam on the iPad, one of the first things I mention is to Save Often, because the app WILL crash on you regularly.  Unfortunately, I haven‚Äôt found a good replacement yet, but I am definitely looking.  One star for giving up on what could be a great product.

I was very excited about the concept of this game.  I found myself rather disappointed.  The stat bonus system is absolutely tedious!  The game has MAJOR balance issues - toward the end equipment doesn‚Äôt even matter since your character stats are enormous in comparison.  All my characters get 1 shot killed and only win by mobbing enemies.  The jobs are ... bad.  Most of these (like merchant, Carpenter etc) should just be aspects of town building.  I don‚Äôt want to fight dragons with merchants, carpenters and ... clowns???  The endgame character class (no need for diversity because it dominates everything) is literally a blockhead.  The present / medal system also silly and tedious.  I wanted to build a town, attract character classes based on how I developed my town (which would five replay value) instead of ‚Äúcollect them all.‚Äù  I was looking forward to the passive nature of this game but found myself constantly sucked into tedious tasks.    Worth a play through but ZERO replay value.  The concept is amazing.  If the developer had consulted to implement better and more traditional rpg mechanics for the characters this could have been such an amazing game.  Turned out kinda mediocre.

If you like synths, get this! One of my faves. Gives awesome crisp modern sounds, but can do a good range in general. There are lots of synths out there, but I feel this one has a character that really sets it apart from others. Kauldron is also a great one from this developer. The two are definitely on my top 8 must-have list.  This synth has so many features, yet it is so well designed that it‚Äôs super straightforward to use. Everything is in the right place. No clutter, yet a lot of controls per page. I usually prefer external fx, but in this synth they really fit in well with the sound.  It‚Äôs hard to pick a best synth in terms of sound because each covers different ground or different approaches to sound design, but in terms of UI it‚Äôs easier to pick because a lot of synths have weak UI. Magellan is definitely at the top, along with Nave - both being beautiful and usable at the same time. Both feel like you have a hardware synth in your hands, and are just a pleasure to use for the eyes, ears, and fingers too.  Only request I have is, please make presets save both synths. There are 2 synth engines that can be used individually or together. You can save each independently and load them, but can‚Äôt save the two combined. Using both engines really gives beautifully huge sound! As a workaround I save them as name-part1, name-part2 so it‚Äôs not really that hard to load the two together later, just think it makes more sense to just treat both synths as a single preset. Oh, and if you could give this synth an AUv3... goes without saying ;)

This synth looks amazing and it‚Äôs easy to modify the sounds and customize things to your liking and it sounds nice through the iPad speakers. Unfortunately when you plug in high quality headphones the sounds are very .... thin. They sound toy-like at best. There is a sound or two that works even with those limitations, and I suppose that‚Äôs worth the $5. But only three stars.

If you love horses or just want a fun game to play, this is definitely the right game for you.

I have tried a lot of the multi-purpose (typing, handwriting, audio and video, import web materials, and presentation) apps, and I like this one the best (by far). Here's why.  1.  The handwriting recognition module (an in-app purchase), called Mazec, is simply the most reliable and easy to use of any offered. 2.  The variety of writing implements offered are easy to access, and the handwriting experience is excellent.  Because of ease of access, it is easy to change implements quickly -- essential for note taking in a fast-paced classroom or lecture environment. 3.  One can use pinch and zoom or bottom zoom for handwriting. Writing with pinch and zoom also has auto scrolling, so you don't get stray lines on your page. 3.  Pages and backgrounds can be imported or created and then made into templates.  Thus, the user has an infinite variety of page backgrounds. 4.  One can cut and paste pages not only between documents, but also between Metamoji apps (for example, between Note and Share). 5. The entire note background (not just the page) can be used for posting photos and typed materials; handwriting can be created on the page and then moved (pasted) on the note background.  Thus the entire canvas (page and note background) can be used. 6. App can accommodate very long notes (over 100 pages) without slowing down.   7. Notes can be stored in a comprehensive filing system using folders and infinite levels of subfolders.   8. Tagging system allows the same note to be stored in several folders at once.  Just add tags corresponding to different folders' names, and the note appears in all the named folders. 9. The app has its own cloud system, Metamoji cloud, which works reliably.  Documents can thus be synced among devices. 10.  The iPhone app is as full-featured as the apps for iPad, and one purchase covers everything.  I am sure that I have forgotten to mention some other crucially important features.  I use this app for everything.  I would probably need several apps in order to do all that this one can do.

I‚Äôve used this app for over 2 years now and a lot has drastically changed.  Pros: You meet language natives of the language you want to learn. It gives you a little bit experience in tutoring your own native language. You get to share cultures with other people. You have the chance to make many friends.  Cons: Sometimes when I take too long to make a post on the moments, Hellotalk automatically restarts and doesn‚Äôt save my progress. Many times, I‚Äôve had this bug issue where friends would send me a message and I would not receive it until way later. Another bug issue is that sometimes I‚Äôm not able to view the moments, messages, or people recommendations because the app is unable to connect.  There are a lot of toxic trolls that have tried to start arguments with me, on my moments posts and they constantly return to any new posts I make. There are a lot of people that don‚Äôt try to exchange language or culture. I‚Äôve gotten few VERY weird messages from both genders, from different countries. Due to the amount of weird, shady, and toxic people on the app; it makes finding friends/language partners, very difficult as a male. The system for moderating the moments is a bit unfair.         ‚ÄîSomeone reported one of my posts for being ‚Äúa dating purpose‚Äù, although that was not my intent nor did I ask any questions for dating on that post. Instead, the post was taken down without question and I got a warning. I have doubts that the post was manually reviewed. I didn‚Äôt even know what the post was, and I had to personally use the in-app messaging to Hellotalk to question what was taken down. Although it was just a warning, I‚Äôve noticed that no one is viewing my educational posts anymore on the moments. So I‚Äôm assuming that I‚Äôm being censored without my own knowledge, considering that I have over 1000 people that follow me because they view my moments as useful for practice and learning.  Overall, the intent of the app‚Äôs goal is admirable; but it is severely lacking in specific areas that cause many good people to voluntarily leave the app.

One problem I‚Äôve often found in many drawing and painting programs, as well as on paper and canvas, is that I tend to have issues with initial sketching.  Something about the process has always felt, somewhat claustrophobic to me, if that makes sense?  What with not knowing exactly how the finished piece will turn out, it begins to feel more and more cramped as more is added to the canvas.  This app, however, completely gets rid of that feeling for me, and allows me to just continue to sketch on and on to my hearts‚Äôs content, without any feeling that I'm running out of space, and then allows me to export my sketches, from which I can then continue and finish them in another program (though, it does seem like you may be able to create good finished pieces here as well, if that better suits your workflow!)  Thank you for this wonderful app!

It is absolutely amazing to me that even after around 2 years of playing this game I am still overcoming new obstacles. This game is EXTREMELY difficult and at sometimes just downright annoying, but that‚Äôs what always kept me coming back and playing again. The main campaign of this game has you backflipping in a unique control scheme that is unlike anything I‚Äôve ever seen before, and there are different unlockable poses that can help you with your backflip, or challenge you. With the added bonus of the ability to ‚Äúcombo‚Äù your positions together allows for what seems like infinite fun. I actually managed to discover how to do a double flip without needing any platforms to jump off of other than the ground with the awesome physics engine that this game has. Also, if you‚Äôre not that into challenge, you can try out the free play mode that lets you experiment with any stage, without lives or basically any restrictions. You can even go into a secret MOON GRAVITY MODE if you tap the screen enough times! And this game basically never crashes, for me, at least, and I‚Äôm using a super old iPad that I just keep updating. On the very small chance that anyone reads this, if you like video games at all, just get this game. It may seem difficult at first, but when you get the hang of it, you open up an entire universe of new possibilities and fun.

I‚Äôve played around a bit with this program and my initial thoughts are very positive! Pros:  - Visiting Town between chapters is entertaining and makes sense.  - Dialogue is expertly crafted, easily better than the ridiculous Japanese-English translation dialogue that plagued FE games - Character portraits and character personalities (so far) are mostly pretty great, with the ocasional hilariously ‚Äúhomemade‚Äù portrait - Special abilities on characters, including support bonuses boosts the depth of combat. Having an accuracy boost on the pathetically weak main character is especially welcome! - Big maps! Some might complain, about more tapping/clicking/turns to traverse, but big maps make battles feel epic!  Cons:  - Punishing EXP system (esp on expert). You will need to grind, especially with your main character, to get them strong enough to not get one shotted by enemy grunts   Tips (for noobs only):  - Exploit the arena. Revisiting town spawns new random arena match - Save your potions! Should be used in arena only - If you run out of potions for the arena, bring in your healer and do 2v2 matches vs. weak enemies to heal your injured units  - For best EXP gains, it is most effective to unequip your character weapon and wait for a weak enemy to attack (and hopefully miss) for 25 turns, OR attack with slow/weak weapons.  (Edit after response from Developers): Bumped up to 4 stars, since the punishing EXP system works as Devs intended!

I do like how every character has a different face, we are able to train before we move onto the next chapter, there are different endings, and the different game play options was pretty neat. Cubasis ‚Äî I guess it‚Äôs an ‚Äòapp‚Äô, but it feels like a real heavy duty piece of software.  Lay out many tracks of audio & midi, use built in sounds & synths, and expand with plugins & samples.  If a sample is a different tempo, time stretch & pitch shift it to fit.  Reminds me a lot of when I first encountered Ableton Live (way back in v4) and I thought, ‚ÄúThis is exactly what I want!‚Äù  Thank you Steinberg - for some people, this is all they will need to make music, record their vocals, add effects, make a pro mix, and export.

Picked up this app about two weeks ago and have really come to grips with the interface. It‚Äôs a powerful piece of software that allows for really easy experimentation and integration/connecting of many different apps including midi generators and AU3 and IAA units.   Lots of routing options allow for some mental combinations. Love using midi generators to control things like the built in drum machines and then recording the midi output.  Playlist is smooth, and zoom is fluid. Would love to see them add: -Time markers -Ability to rearrange tracks (update: added) -Group track lanes into folders that can collapse to help free up small screen space -Song sections to quickly rearrange song parts (intro, verse, etc).  Also something is off with the piano roll. I often find myself either accidentally drawing a note when trying to pinch to zoom, deleting a note when trying to move it, and not drawing a note because the draw button reset back to off position. Other than that the piano roll itself is fluid.
Still waiting for a proper drum device that lets me use my own samples and offers effective note repeat comparable to BeakMaker 3

The first 60% of this game is a beautifully stylistic roguelite RPG with an interesting set of classes and abilities, a strange but intriguing storyline, and a punishing but fair level of difficulty which requires you to make your moves very precisely. I loved it.  Then the bizarro portals came.  The last 40% of the game is an RNGfest where strategic planning goes out the window and you just have to pray to RNGesus that multiple portals don‚Äôt end up getting placed close together and drown you in an endless flood of bizarro enemies. You‚Äôre forced to restart levels over and over again until the procedural-generation finally doesn‚Äôt screw you, and then for a brief, wonderful moment you‚Äôre back to playing the game you loved. Then you move to the next floor and it‚Äôs another coin flip.  I‚Äôd love to know how this quirky story ends, but it‚Äôs not worth wading through the RNG chaos of the last couple levels. Ok maybe it‚Äôs 4.5 star but I was really impressed by how helpful the app was in planning the diet. Now for the cons: - I‚Äôm vegetarian+fish and I had to eliminate all meat items one by one; considering the number of vegetarian users, I recommend a preference to eliminate all meat (and all fish for the strictly vegetarian) during initial setup; - accessing the meal map tab, it should bring you by default to today‚Äôs date, I grew tired of browsing through the week every time (the my day tab doesn‚Äôt cover all functionalities one has in the meal map) - it would be nice if the app interfaced to Apple Health at least to automatically read my weight data  By the way the diet works like magic, couldn‚Äôt shed as much weight if I skipped all meals.

Based on the great reviews I read, I was really excited to play this game.  However, after about 5 hours of playing, I‚Äôm perplexed why people rate this game so highly. There doesn‚Äôt seem to be any rhyme or reason to the consequences of your actions (sometimes you make a seemingly logical choice and you die; others times you pick something whimsical and get rewarded with treasure).  The spell book mechanics are awkward, forcing you to flip back and forth between menus to try to figure out which spell might help in a given situation.  And the storyline is a bit too linear for my taste, not allowing you to go back and explore areas you have previously been too.  Thank god I bought this game a couple years after it‚Äôs release, so I only wasted $5 on it.  Avoid at all costs.

In the first installment, I felt as though I was really choosing my own adventure ‚Äî there were so many things I knew I was missing as I blundered my way through which really made the game feel magical and unique, and made me want to replay it to see what I‚Äôd missed. In this one, you have to wander aimlessly through a city, covering every inching and getting thrown backwards or killed at any ‚Äúwrong‚Äù step. You‚Äôre forced to collect 4 spell lines, ensuring that you experience the exact same things every time. I felt as though I was being railroaded by a storyteller who insisted on me playing through one particular story. What‚Äôs the point of a ‚Äúchoose your adventure‚Äù that forces you to choose the one right path?

I went over the four apps in my review of the first book, I‚Äôll just add a few things. Again Inkle has enhanced an old, classic gamebook and created a fantastic game. This second volume is far superior to the first one‚Äîit takes a long time to understand what‚Äôs going on, to gather all the clues that you need to succeed, although it is also the continuation of the previous volume. It can seem sometimes it will be difficult to finish it but it is never impossible, and the rich universe that lies behind the story is full of mysteries and twists and keeps you involved. A must-have.

All you have to do is press ‚ÄúStart‚Äù and a workout will be loaded for you that takes into account what muscles you worked on the day before, as well as your goals/difficulty. I can think of many things that can be done to make this app more dynamic and adaptable instead of just a simple app that acts as a log and sends you preset reminders. The most obvious one is to change your required daily intake based on your level of activity. iPhones and Apple Watches log your basic level of activity (distance walked, flights climbed, number of steps) and many people log their physical activity into the health app using different apps and activity trackers. Wouldn‚Äôt it be cool if the app accounted for that and upped your required water intake based on your level of activity each day? Other things the app can adapt for can be weight and body water % (I use a smart scale that automatically calibrates this info to my health app), weather (like a reminder to drink extra water on a hot day), and consumption of diuretic drinks as logged into the app. If the developers can incorporate these features into the app then they would really have a complete app that stands out from the rest.

The concept and general gameplay is really great but the satellite mission controls don‚Äôt seem to work quite right.  Four control thrusters are required to yaw because it uses the left/right thruster to do this motion. This can just as easily be achieved with the forward/rear thrusters utilizing only two.  The above issue causes several problems. 1) Uses fuel quicker. 2) Requires an understanding of center of balance when there are no indicators where that could possibly be. No weights or dimensions of the parts are provided much less an accurate tool to locate the thrusters on the correct part of the body. This results in unintended yaw when trying to maneuver left and right which causes unintended yaw.  Additionally, there is no way to turn the control thrusters off for other portions of the flight. This means your burning control thruster fuel the entire flight and by the time you‚Äôve aligned with the satellite you‚Äôre low or out of control thruster fuel.   Finally, the controls for fine maneuvering do not respond correctly. The forward button works as intended, tap it, hold it and the ship moves as you would expect. The back, left, right, and yaw controls don‚Äôt. You have to hold them down before that do anything, at which point they start burning hard, creating uncontrolled movement.  Add this together and it turns ‚Äúchallenging‚Äù into wholly frustrating.  I am loath to try the Simple Planes as I imagine it relies heavily on The maneuvering controls and would have related issues.

I am not sure if there is more than 1 ending so I was going to go through it again. But the one I got was less than satisfying. There are plenty of common tropes that could have worked better.  So in summary, a as game it is so-so, as an experience it is excellent.

I have 4 SoundTouch 10's and one SoundTouch 300. I love using this app, but at the same time, I experience some frustrations with it. It really could use some fixes and enhancements:  1. When using SoundTouch to access my Deezer account, and referencing My Library, it does NOT alphabetize the list. I have long lists of Artists and Albums. I have to read through the entire list to find what I am looking for, so it takes a while. That's quite inconvenient. The separate Deezer app does alphabetize these same lists; the SoundTouch app just needs to do that, too. 2. When playing an album with the Deezer service, after a while I can no longer user the left arrow to return to the list of songs on the album. I have to go to the artist's page, then find the album again. 3. When selecting a speaker for SoundTouch to use, I would like the ability to rearrange the order of the speakers (I have 5) so that they would be listed in the app in the order I want. One of my preferences would be to place my primary speaker (SoundTouch 30)  as the first one listed, so it is the first one to appear when I go to the speaker panels.  If I can do it this way, I won't have to swipe through the list to reach my primary speaker every time I'm turning it on for switching music. 4. While swiping through the list of speakers, the app often jumps back to the first speaker in the list, fighting my efforts to choose a speaker other than the first one. 5. When playing on multiple synchronized speakers, and I return to the listing of speakers in the group, sometimes the volume slider for one of the speakers appears in the wrong position. When this happens, the slider is positioned much lower than what is the actual setting. 6. I would like to have more presets. An idea I have for implementing this, using current hardware, is to allow pressing two number keys on the speaker. For example, additional presets could be 11, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 21, 22, 22, etc. I'm assuming this could be accomplished in the software/firmware. 7. I can't find a way to submit product enhancement suggestions and bug reports to Bose. The mechanism may exist, but I can't find it. The Feedback section was updated with more questions, and the ability to enter text comments. However, the text area allows only a few sentences, then cuts off the rest (I tried to paste in 7 issues and suggestions, with explanations for each one.) Most companies have an email address or web page for this. If I could find a means to do that, I wouldn't be posting these problems and suggestions in the App Store review. 8. While playing music using the Deezer service, I was in the Feedback area in the app, and entering the comments. I had to switch to another app to check my notes. When I returned, the feedback page was gone, and I was left with the Deezer page, but with the top of the page missing: no buttons, and no Deezer name. I had to close and reopen the app to fix it. 9. I would like the option to select the music first and then the speakers second. Currently, if I want to play some music through multiple speakers, I have to first select one speaker, then select the music, then go back to the list of speakers and add the additional speakers to the streaming. Therefore, I would like the option to select the music, then select the speaker or speakers. That would be much more convenient. It would be fine to keep the existing method as an alternative.

They stopped asking for more money so I moved it up to 3 stars.   I have been using this app for a long time and paid for it in the beginning. Below, you can read my original glowing review.  However, the developers have done virtually nothing since then to improve the app and I have found it to be very unstable, frequently crashing and losing my annotations.  I was happy to see an update pop up for it a few days ago, however instead of improving it this update just makes the app harass me to pay for a subscription to use their new updated version of the app.  This is ridiculous, especially since I already paid for this app!  If you want split screen in a PDF reader, get easy annotate.  For other stuff, go with any app that doesn't crash constantly and doesn't try to get more money from you after you already paid for their product.  If they want to switch to a subscription model, fine, but give a free subscription to the people who bought your app when you were just getting started.  If you won't do that, you have no integrity and deserve to crash and burn!  I have been using the free version of this app which is a reader only for quite a while because it is by far the fastest I have seen.  Meanwhile I have hunted everywhere for split screen PDF apps.  I have side by side which is nice but can't annotate.  I have Easy Annotate which has great potential but which I find slow and temperamental as well as having issues with annotating text in languages that put some characters above and below others.  Recently I learned that this app had added a spit screen view.  I decided to get it and am very impressed.  As a PDF viewer, annotating app, this is the best I have used.  The highlight tool works great in any language I have tried.  Split screen is excellent and easy to use.  File management is functional and easy to navigate.  This is not a media player, browser, Swiss Army knife but it is a great pdf app.  Why only 4 stars then?  There are a few minor things that could be improved.   1. Simplify the highlighter color selection.  I don't need a million color choices.  I do need about 5 good distinct colors that can be easily changed.  The implementation is not terrible, but would be much better if everything but a simple selection of preferred colors was under a secondary menu. 2. Any time you are annotating, the undo, redo buttons should be visible.  Right now, they are often not. 3. The file outline and bookmarks need to be accessible in split screen mode. 4. The underline feature looks excellent, however it is not in the same menu as the highlight option or as easy to use.  It would be really nice if those two options and their color selections were together and if you could underline as easily as you can highlight. Thanks for a great app.  I will be recommending it to many people and will love it even more if you can implement these suggestions.

About a month ago, I opened the package and it wouldn‚Äôt work. When I tried to edit or redact, it offered me a ‚Äúfree trial‚Äù teaser leading to a $50/year subscription.   I tried ‚Äúrestore purchases‚Äù which didn‚Äôt work, then contacted Readdle. We‚Äôve been back and forth on this for 3 weeks, but their final message on the topic appears to be ‚ÄúScrew you.‚Äù  It is unimaginable to me that a company would ‚Äúupgrade‚Äù a software package (named PDF EDITOR), removing its core capability, and try to get me to pay an outrageous upcharge to restore the functionality that I ALREADY PAID FOR. If you do your research and scour the internet (or the App Store Page) for reviews on this game, you‚Äôll see that most of the reviews label the game as hard. That‚Äôs a complete lie. This game isn‚Äôt hard... it‚Äôs slow.  None of the Kairosoft games are hard. You can‚Äôt ‚Äúlose‚Äù in these games. You just earn far less than you spend in this one. Structures cost upwards of a hundred dollars and you only earn 100 or 200 IF you win a race... and sometimes you won‚Äôt.   The given allowance is spent quickly on new horses and training structures. It‚Äôs not reliable unless you‚Äôre content with saving a lot (of money).  Maintenance costs about 100+ early game and it‚Äôs a constant cycle, so if you don‚Äôt win at least once before the next cycle, you‚Äôll be in the negatives. In addition, items cost upwards of 100 as well. Prices rise the more items you buy.  And of course there‚Äôs the obvious concern: horse lifespans. A horse is done by year four. Their stats decrease so they‚Äôll lose the race ‚Äî and if you don‚Äôt make first place, you get less than $100. Races can‚Äôt be scheduled rapidly either. So you don‚Äôt get paid rapidly ‚Äî only in $100 chunks once per month.  People coming to your ranch spend about $10-20 and only come when you‚Äôve won ‚Äî if you lose your streak, you lose your only source of constant income.  Selling a horse gives you about $1000. But then you spend that $1000 on another horse.  Therefore, in order to progress, you must manage your funds carefully‚Äî meaning months or even years without spending anything on any major progression. The secondary currency, coins, can‚Äôt be spent often since you have to discover an upgrade before buying it.  Races are fun but become mediocre after hours of them. Even when you win. Since horses are temporary and you don‚Äôt unlock breeding until late game, you have to level up your horse faster than the previous one or you‚Äôll just be stuck. You‚Äôll have hit a wall.  The three stars I rate here are basically fueled by my love of horses and the sales price of $0.99, which were barely enough to keep me interested. No wonder the $0.99 sale has stayed past December (winter sales). I was drawn in by that sale. But don‚Äôt be fooled ‚Äî unless you like progressing at a crawl or you love horses enough to be okay with many, many races before you progress.

UPDATE 6: It‚Äôs now October 2017. I reloaded this game onto my iPhone 6S Plus to see if the developer made any improvements with the recent iOS 11 update. Answer: NO! The game still freezes randomly when the blob that you‚Äôre manipulating through the maze gets stuck on an obstacle. Already deleted the game from my phone. It‚Äôs a shame they never fixed this glaring glitch. But look on the bright side: the pop-up ads still work great!  STRONGLY NOT RECOMMENDED!   UPDATE 5: It's now September 2016. Yes, the game is still off of my new iPhone 6s Plus. I'm reading more current reviews that have expressed the same frustration I expressed over a year ago with this game. Sad that the developers won't listen to the reviews and make the appropriate improvements to the game. Will check back in another year to see if improvements have been implemented. Out.  UPDATE 4: It's now one year later since my last review, and the game is still deleted off of my iPhone. Looks like more recent reviews are echoing what I stated in my original reviews from a couple years ago. Sad.  UPDATE 3: The game still has glitches where you get hung up on an obstacle and can't get off of it which causes you to lose your life and have to start all over at the beginning. Not sure why the developer will not address this issue. I did see that the developer was pretty quick to install ads and things like that, so I don't know why they won't fix the gameplay bugs. As soon as I finish typing this, I'm deleting the app from my phone. Do not buy and download less you like buggy gameplay that's very frustrating and a lot of ads.   DEFINITELY NOT RECOMMENDED!  UPDATE 2: As others have pointed out, I also have been experiencing bugs in the game where I get hung up on one of the obstacles. When this happens, you cannot move off of the obstacle and you have to wait until the timer runs out and you die. This is very frustrating when you gotten so far in the game and then can't move anymore because you're stuck on an obstacle.  The developer has still not addressed the issue of having to always restart back at the very beginning when you die. This combined with the bugs is making this game very frustrating. I'm on the verge of deleting this game from my iPhone. I'm changing my final analysis to:  NOT RECOMMENDED  UPDATE: This game is still fun to play; however, it is too difficult. I've been playing for the last couple of weeks and still cannot get past the third level. It's very, very frustrating when you die and have to go all way back to the beginning. If this issue is not addressed in an update, I will be deleting this game from my iPhone for good. Not worth the frustration, the aggravation, the waste of time, and the lack of a sense of accomplishment.  This game is very fun to play and very creative. The soundtrack is also enjoyable as are the graphics. I hope the developer continues to develop this game and make it more complex by adding more levels, more obstacles, more power ups, and more overall challenge. Great job so far!  Highly recommended.

This app needs a Product designer with a focus on Customer Experience.   I have been writing a History book packed  dates and headers. This requires only 3 levels of hierarchy and the appropriate spacing between the headers and between the body to create the right visual relationship so that it‚Äôs scannable.  However there is just one very large distance for the line height,  between all of the headers. There is no way to adjust the gap height, between headers H1, H2, H3 etc... or body.    It‚Äôs always a double return amount of space. I don‚Äôt know what you call it in Markup. But I just want the character size to be different, with a simple return to the next line. I don‚Äôt need a giant double spaced gap between each header.   If I don‚Äôt separate with a double return, then the body gets grouped into the header.  A simple 1 return doesn‚Äôt have any effect. In the editor it looks like it‚Äôs a new line, but I you go to the publish view all the text runs together as if it‚Äôs part of the header. It‚Äôs the Same with all the H‚Äôs. I managed to make it kind of work with H3 and H4. If I could paste their format into H2 and H3, maybe I could get some use from this.  The other problem is return doesn‚Äôt return. It‚Äôs really a pin to go through and add a double space to every line. If I don‚Äôt then it groups all the text into header. The Only way to get the body back down to body size is the space and double return, and then there are all these giant gaps between every date and location. Which is about every 8-20 lines. Probably no big deal for a developer. But for someone whose trying to write content, not code. It‚Äôs a real pain.  The other problem, is the *preview button* keeps going away and there is no way to pull it up except poke around on the top of the screen. So every time I want to check if it‚Äôs formatted correctly I have to tap around to try to find the hidden button. Of coarse then my curser has selected some other line of text and things start popping off, and then the whole page starts scrolling to the top loosing my place.  This really ruins the experience for me, because now, when the button finally appears, I‚Äôm buried somewhere in the middle of 18,000 -30,000 words. Trying to find my way back is a real pain =(. It makes it impossible to concentrate on what I‚Äôm actually trying to do, >write.    The #1 goal I have is to write and markup my sections so the dates and titles are easily scannable. I didn‚Äôt buy the software so I could ‚Äúplay‚Äù with the cool apps features.   I know how difficult it is build an app. But I feel like the Users goals are left out the build process here and instead all the energy went into engineering and implementing  ‚Äúfeatures for developers‚Äù.  I guess it‚Äôs not for long form writers. I don‚Äôt know what I can use to format this project. I feel like email or notes works the best, but they just can‚Äôt handle that much text.  I give 3 stars just because there is so much potential in this app and I really hope they can hire some UX help to figure out what writers want to do (not just devs). And there is a lot of thoughtfulness in it, so I‚Äôm hopeful basic formatting will improve.  But for me it‚Äôs currently not even as useful as the notes app. Which breaks my heart. Because I know how hard it is to build something like this.
