UPDATED UPDATE: This developer proves that his feature-rich approach to inputting text is brilliant. But Nintype still fails to properly interpret many common words. (This technology, pioneered by IBM and eventually migrated to iOS in the long-discontinued Shapewriter, should have been perfected by now!)  UPDATED REVIEW... Very pleased to see this remarkable keyboard finally updated! It now seems more accurate, perhaps even much more accurate! But I must refresh my memory to recall all of its many features! Thanks to the developer for returning to fix his creation. This is one of those apps that you are thrilled to discover, yet are constantly frustrated by it. Every keyboard should have at least a fraction of its clever features. But they don't. Unfortunately, Nintype is unable to fulfill its most basic requirement. After many trials, it seems unable to reliably interpret gesture text-entry, even after giving it time to train itself. A shame!

Been using this since it first came out. It‚Äôs an off and on off again relationship honestly. Before I stopped using the keyboard because of the constant crashes and memory leaks associated with such an advanced keyboard. But it‚Äôs been well worth it. Texting and even doing essays with this style of keyboard is amazing and satisfying. It‚Äôs realist gratifying once you get the swing of things.   Newest update has made Nintype more stable than ever with almost no crashes ever. I can‚Äôt even remember the last time the keyboard would crash at all.   Now the only complaint and a very minute one at that, is that the little mini game that comes with nintype is almost unplayable. It‚Äôs very glitchy and holding the spacebar to charge the bump to the next word doesn‚Äôt really work correctly anymore.   Ultimately though that‚Äôs really a dumb and minor issue to have, but it‚Äôs a good example of how great this keyboard truly is. If this is the only issue now then it just shows how awesome nintype has become. Texting, and writing notes on your phone especially in landscape mode is a breeze and it‚Äôs amazing truly how fast you can eventually type with this keyboard. Not to mention the haptic feedback and themes you can customize and apply just adds even more content to an already amazing keyboard. Seriously a good job. Can‚Äôt ever go back to a regular touch keyboard again.

Out of all the keyboards that are currently out there, this is by far the best keyboard. It brings something new to the table and requires you to put some effort into learning how to use it, but once you do it‚Äôs a breeze. It looks awesome and actually feels like a smart keyboard. Once you get the hang of it, typing feels effortless and smooth. The biggest problem is after a while the keyboard is constantly restarting, making it unusable. This I believe is more on Apple than the developer because this problem has affected every 3rd party keyboard I have used. It‚Äôs disappointing because I love this keyboard but until Apple fixes its sh*tty platform I won‚Äôt be able to use it consistently. At this rate, I‚Äôm just going to switch to Android given how iOS hasn‚Äôt had a substantial update since Steve passed.

This is the only iOS app for which I have paid, and I am glad I did. I use it daily, and regularly in about 10 languages. The app handles long blocks of text well. CONS: Speech to Text and Speech to Speech do not work reliably; sometimes they do not work at all, while others produce an ‚ÄúInternet connection too slow‚Äù message, even though it runs at over 100 Mbps. Much of the time I get nonsense for dictated speech. WISHLIST: 1. Having several choices for single words would be good, as words can have several senses. However, the app almost always gets it right. 2. A list longer than the 4 previous ‚ÄúRecently Used‚Äù languages would be a timesaver, or the option to select a longer list. (I just suggested this to the developers.)

My daughter loves this.  Its incredible how well this teaches phonetic (and sight) reading.  It definitely requires parental guidance though; do not send kids off to play this by themselves.  This program builds up new skills and sight words FAST, often using sight words that the student hasn‚Äôt seen as the answer (it‚Äôs a good thing; students figure them out by process of elimination and are never shown two new words at once and are required to recall or sound out multiple previously seen words ).  By comparison, ABCmouse seems galacially paced.  Most kids will do better if an adult is there to help them walk through the words when they forget a skill or get confused.

I hope Scanbot Pro can reasonably reduce the price in half, because with the availability of free apps and in-app purchases, few people would pay monthly for a scanner.

This is Peggle, but with EA's grimy hands all over the product. As a Peggle lover from the Pop Cap only days, I was excited to have Peggle on my phone to play anywhere I wanted, and for a while overlooked the Candy Crush like elements of the mobile version.  I un-installed at level 38. I had been trying to beat this level for a day, and had to wait for my lives to restock to try again. Three lives in, and I finally cleared every orange peg. Excited to move onto the next level, the game had informed me I failed because I didn't score enough points.  That isn't only "difficulty for difficulty's sake", which I can handle because it makes the eventual victory sweeter, but when you combine that with a lives system that encourages me to spend actual money, I'm out. I not only have to clear orange pegs, difficult enough, but now I have to make sure to have enough points too?   Pop Cap made the best small, addicting games and I basically threw money at them to get their gaming version of drugs. Now, with EA, I can't uninstall fast enough.
EA makes really good games. Unfortunately, they are also an unconscionably greedy company.

This is a FANTASTIC game, and if you've never played it yet, you should most definitely grab it. I snagged the early access version on Steam and WOW! SO. MUCH. HAS. BEEN. ADDED!!! It's almost like a sequel (well, ATM, it's basically a Wayward Souls 1.5)!!!  I REALLY hope your team is able to add all of this new content to the iPhone build. Seeing as how we've all been playing the iPhone version for, what, 5 years now... I'm pretty sure that most all of us have gotten accustomed to the touchscreen controls. Even after playing with a controller on my laptop for over 6 months now, it still doesn't feel EXACTLY right, and I don't think there's anything that could be done to make it so.   Anyway.... if you're an Action RPG fan, or a sucker for sadistically difficult games :;: GET THIS. NOW!!  The touchscreen controls are spot on perfect, and I do believe they have MFi support as well (I don't know, the current version has an OS requirement too high for my iPhone 5, which is the only device that fits in my MOGA controller - so I couldn't tell you). It's an iOS classic, and if I wasn't so emotionally attached to Secret of Mana, it'd be my #1 favorite ARPG available.   To the devs:;: PLEASE PLEASE PLEASE include your mobile customers when you officially release all of the new content!! Raise the price! I'd very gladly gift this game to quite a few people that share base-reality with me, even if I knew they weren't going to enjoy it. I also have a few very close friends in other countries I would love to share it with on Steam - so once it goes live after it's early access, you can count on me buying them copies as well, regardless of wether or not the new content is brought over to mobile. You all deserve every single sale you get and then some. THANK YOU FOR CREATING THIS MAGNIFICENT GAME!

Classy.  Anyway, what‚Äôs going on with the Now Kollection consists of what I‚Äôm already wearing, and when I navigate to it, I wind up at a blank page I can‚Äôt close, or it just crashes the app? This has gone untreated for two days or more.  More universal concerns: no reliable way to change operating systems. As everyone reading this is likely aware, iOS goes through periods of being enraging or unusable. Since this game also exists on Android, I don‚Äôt understand why I can‚Äôt play the same account on Android sometimes while iOS has one of those several-month-long user-hostility tantrums. Maybe fix this right away too.  Not as important to me because I‚Äôm dull and basic: only two genders and only one body type for each. Disappointing in 2018 (UPDATE: it‚Äôs now mid-2019 and the closest thing to a solution is that some of the dresses for female characters falsely simulate the gentle hint of modest curves) especially when female characters can have the same clothes as (voluptuous and body-positive) Kim Kardashian but have to remain stick-thin no matter what. Strange comparison to incessantly bludgeon the user with.  UPDATE: The UX has somehow found a way to be MORE of a nightmare? If you‚Äôre a loyal player like I am, you probably have a lot of clothes and accessories. When taking part in contests like Show Your Style, it would be nice to have a few quality-of-life improvements to make organization a lot easier (read: it is essential that drastic changes be made immediately). There used to be a grey tag on clothes that you had just submitted that let you know at a glance what you would have to wait a couple days to use again. That tag has been missing from the past two Show Your Style contests. The tag is not enough to keep navigating the vast and cumbersome sufficiently user-friendly, but removing it was a stupid mistake and it needs to come back before I log back into the game in a few minutes. Also, an undo button cannot be implemented quickly enough (refer to imvu to see how it‚Äôs done), because as you navigate, the game misinterprets a TON of touch screen dragging as taps. Also, Accessories and Miscellany absolutely must, as soon as possible, be further subdivided into earrings, necklaces, rings, left wrist, right wrist, et cetera. Lastly (FOR NOW), let‚Äôs have one of those elevator thingies on the side of long, scrolling menus, that let you easily tell how far down a too-long list you‚Äôve navigated. Like... every app with a long list of characters or cards or whatever has one of these things. Microsoft Word has utilized this feature for decades and the fact that the Kardashian game doesn‚Äôt have one is felt like a gunshot in your shoulder.  So fix these mistakes like quick. Like literally before tomorrow. Then we can talk about other no-brainer quality-of-life necessities this game has somehow SURVIVED FIVE YEARS without providing.  (To be clear, nobody should be taking part in Show Your Style until the UX is fixed. I know I won‚Äôt, and I also know that I‚Äôve spent quite a bit of money to take part in Show Your Style, so I genuinely hope that a good boycott acts as a game-fixing gadfly to these greedy developers.)  UPDATE: Need more of a warning that there‚Äôs a special event on than a vague, solitary, and missable push notification that merely mentioned that Fashion Week is happening. Also I‚Äôm pretty sure that the push came hours after the event had started. Why not let us know a few days in advance that an event is coming up? Or, like the games that are doing this right are doing, a week or more in advance?

I really liked this game. For me it somehow had a big realm atmosphere for such a relatively small game, perhaps due to nice music, a smattering of decent sound effects, smooth 3D travel, a quick travel map, great graphics, and a good dose of subtle humor in many of the descriptions (kinda reminded me of some old text adventures). I found the puzzles to be well varied, pretty logical, and mostly intuitive. A couple extra slider puzzles, yes, but didn‚Äôt mind them til I got to the end. Honestly, that one was about as much fun as putting together a jigsaw puzzle with the same picture on both sides. Other than that, only got stumped a couple times, but pushed through without the hints and felt pretty satisfied when I finished, except for the lack of closure with the end story. No matter; after all, I wasn‚Äôt reading a novel, just playing a short, entertaining puzzle game, and I‚Äôm glad I did.

I did not find that there were to many sliding puzzles in this game. I found a diversity of fetching items to unlock doors and mechanical sliding puzzles. The last puzzle was an absolute nightmare but it was so satisfying to solve. I recommend this game for puzzle adventure enthusiasts.

Let‚Äôs get the big topic out of the way. This game is a money milking machine. Natural Motion or the big dogs up top known as Zynga are some of the worst in the mobile gaming market. Don‚Äôt get me wrong it aligns up perfectly with its competition being NFS no limits and Asphalt 9. Both of which are just as bad in terms of ‚Äúmilking it‚Äù.  So let‚Äôs go into detail as to why I‚Äôm leaving this 2 star review. I doubt it‚Äôll matter but here it goes. I was a hardcore player for several months. I enjoyed the game a lot and I had a great crew. That was until Natural Motion started shoving more paid events into the game. As time went on most of my crew mates grew tired of having to pay to complete certain events. Natural Motion decided to ramp up the difficultly on the free to play events so people are more inclined to spend money.  Practically everything has became a paid event at this point because you‚Äôre either locked out until you buy a certain car or you‚Äôre stuck in an event due to the difficulty increase. Natural Motion believes this is what players want. They believe that this is fair. Speaking of fair let‚Äôs discuss my most recent discussion with their in game support team.  In the past I paid for some fate of the furious cars. Enough of them to complete the ice charger event. I spent a good amount of resources to complete it as well. I won the car and at the time I had it nearly maxed out. Like I said before I was having trouble with my crew. I burnt through all my resources and no one was active enough to help me build them back up. I started losing seasonal milestone cars and then rewards because they were leaving.   Just recently I decided I wanted to start a new save file not taking into account that I should probably write down my previous player ID. When I got through with the tutorial I realized my fate of the furious cars that I paid money for were returned to me (without upgrades S6s or fusions). I went to share this on the official Sub Reddit where someone suggested I ask support about getting my ice charger back as I did pay money to complete the event (had to buy the cars to be able to play in it) seeing as I owned all the cars I used for the event on this new account I figured it was worth a shot.   I contacted support and told them in very clear detail that I had changed save files and would like my ice charger back going over that I had the other cars on my account and I was suggested to bring it up by some other players. Support got back to me with the response of ‚Äúwe don‚Äôt give out free cars as we focus on keeping the game fair for everyone. Keep an eye out for future offers‚Äù <- (this means give us your money)  Anyways to end off with my 2 star review I‚Äôd like to make a statement. This game isn‚Äôt fair what so ever. A good majority of the top players are well known hackers and cheaters yet Natural Motion and Zynga do absolutely nothing about it. They proceed to shove paid events down your throat and raise the difficulty level of events overtime so more people are forced to pay if they want to finish these events. The only thing fair is the fact that most players along with myself are tired of this crap.   If you think Natural Motion or Zynga needs your money do not worry as they‚Äôre already filthy stinking rich.

The input is very intuitive, more so than another notation app I bought for iPad. Unfortunately, after paying for it I discovered too many bugs which have not yet been addressed.  1. Copy and paste function is terrible!  When copying a bar to another bar it doesn‚Äôt put the notes where they were in the copied measure, they get transposed all differently depending on where you touch the screen, so you have to sort of guess where to tap the screen, and if you guessed wrong, which you probably will do most of the time, you have to copy all over again and try to paste in the right spot, which is ridiculous.  PLEASE FIX THIS!!!  2. Playback tool is too limited.  This should be more like a standard playback tool with rewind and fast-forward controls not just play and stop.  Also there should be a way to have it play back in swing like other notation programs can.   3.  The sound is buggy. Sometimes it just doesn‚Äôt work, and the only way to get it back is for me to restart my iPad. I shouldn‚Äôt have to do that, the sound should be more robust than that.  4.  There are some basic articulation‚Äôs and phrase markings which don‚Äôt exist in this app, such as marcato, falls, and glissando.  I would be happy to write a more positive review if these items could be addressed and if the maker or makers of this software would show more interest in supporting it with more frequent updates as these problems are brought to their attention by users like myself who actually paid for it.

This game has been my literal no-brainer game for several years. It‚Äôs small and simple design has kept me coming back for more. The occasional changes in landscape, be it a cactus, a cloud, a color shift, brought an element of satisfaction simply because of their rarity. It was a joy to see something new. A reminder of how pleasant the simple things of life can be.   However, upon reaching hole 10,000 today at 26,476 strokes, something new I did not expect occurred. Hole 10,001 did not generate. Instead I found myself on the shore of an endless ocean. Hmm, I thought. Perhaps it‚Äôs a fluke? So I rebooted the app and there was still no new hole. I hit the ball into the ocean, and the ball vanished beneath the water and did not regenerate again. I no longer have a ball to hit. Nor a hole to shoot for. The game promised infinity, but the game literally ending like this exactly at hole 10,000 seems like it‚Äôs an ending by design. If not, the game has broken at hole 10,001 and I‚Äôd like to keep playing. As far as endings go, I will say this does seem like a very appropriate ending for this simple game.

I keep thinking Transistor (one of my favorites of all time) in a dual-stick shooter format. This game is so good, they could have asked for a lot more in terms of price; it's a steal. My only complaint (and I hope the devs are reading this) is that the camera is a bit too sensitive to every movement. When you've got to do a lot of dodging, it can be a bit jarring. I think it could be easily smoothed over in an update (it's certainly not a deal breaker nor does it take away from gameplay). Anyway, amazing job, Devs. Thank you for making this amazing game and thanks for bringing it to iOS!  Update: I still adore this amazing shooter but I‚Äôd love to see iPhone XR screen compatibility. I loved this game on Mac and now playing through it on hard difficulty on iOS. Unfortunately I encountered this gamebreaking bug: after the first fight in the first war, the gray screen appears with a clickable arrow to go on to the following fight. I spent a long time carefully orchestrating a good strategy that took a good anount of time to plan and play out, maybe 25 minutes. The arrow on the gray screen however wasn‚Äôt clickable and the game essentially was stuck; I tried anything I could think of like rotating the iPhone screen, tapping home button then coming back to the app, tapping and swiping anywhere...to no avail. When i hard exited the app from the OS and restarted it, as knew would happen, the war progress is gone and I need to start from the last auto save; very frustrating after a long, hard fight that had gone well and I don‚Äôt think I‚Äôm going to try it again after a while given it seems like it‚Äôll just hang again...  This game is a wonderful work of art and a great accomplishment in terms of game design, artwork, music, and I find it very unfortunate that a few polish issues got by the quality assurance that really interrupt the flow and immersion. I actually encountered this exact bug on the Mac Desktop version, but in that case alt tabbing out and back took care of it. I have a hard time believing this somehow never came up in testing and somehow wasn‚Äôt taken care of. I‚Äôm on iPhone 6 by the way.   My actual rating for this game is more like 4+ stars, but I am currently frustrated at the loss of progress, and it would certainly be 5 stars if bugs like didn‚Äôt appear, as well as some small improvements to the display that I wrote about in a rewiew of BS2: when displaying all armor / str flags in combat, surround enemy flags by a red outline to make them stand out from your own heroes more and make it easier to parse information; add a second buttton that when pressed shows numbers next to the enemy units on the battlefield representing their turn order: 1 for next, 2 for one after that etc. These small quality of life improvements to help display information and the player parse said information that is already available,more easily would make the game more of a pleasure to play, for me personally.

You buy the game. You play it. No servers, no log-ins, no in-app purchases, no excessive layers of currencies and pay-to-win mechanics. I had nearly forgotten phone games could be this straightforward. I bought this on a whim after the release of ‚ÄúHero‚Äù in Smash Bros. reminded me of the original game (which was called ‚ÄúDragon Warrior‚Äù in the U.S., in case anyone is looking for that game). Very happy with the purchase.  The game itself is very old school. You‚Äôll be doing a lot of grinding, but the touch screen menus make that more tolerable and it‚Äôs a decent enough way to pass the time. Most phone games force you into grinding anyway, but suggest you pay money to skip it. In this one you‚Äôll just have to slash away at slimes until you level up to take on better enemies like the old days. The overworld controls are a little goofy, like all phone d-pads, but they get the job done and finesse is not needed in this kind of game. I like the vertical orientation; it makes it easier to switch in and out of the app to do stuff on your phone without having to turn the whole phone.  The updated graphics and music give the game a cool SNES vibe. I‚Äôd love the option to use the original graphics/music/screen resolution, but I can see how that might be infeasible given the phone layout. In any case, love has clearly been given to this port, and if you like ‚Äò80s JRPGs, this is well worth your $3. I‚Äôll probably play through the series and see if I can convince myself to check out DQ11 for Switch eventually.

The hifi files on Tidal are noticeably better than the crap on Spotify and I sprang for a subscription as soon as I heard one. Although the catalog is a bit more limited, it contains almost anything if you know how to look. But that‚Äôs not easy, especially if you‚Äôre interested in anything outside of mainstream pop. Like maybe classical. Do a search for Felix Mendelssohn, for example, and it returns about two dozen albums of the ‚Äúclassical moods‚Äù variety, stuff by b-list performers. But search for the Emerson Quartet, and you will find their recording of Mendelssohn‚Äôs octet, and others. You have to search by performer. If you want to compare recordings of a particular composition, you have to make a list of them from some other source. Like maybe Spotify. This really limits Tidal‚Äôs usefulness as a music discovery tool, and although I really like the service, I can‚Äôt give it a higher rating than 3.

Review of Tidal Hifi. This sound quality is great. Not only are you getting lossless audio, you also get proper dynamic range (0-100Db)! This has taken me by surprise. For example, a song suddenly exploded after sounding a little soft. That's how music was mean't to be heard. Even if you choose "high" instead of "HiFi", you still get the same dynamic range.  One thing I would like is Siri support. This way, I can ask Siri to play a song and she'll play it on Tidal.

This app is very good at what it does, but it presents a bug when used with the Apple Watch. If your watch is in one language (such as English) and you try to dictate a message in another language (such as Japanese) on your watch, the watch incorrectly interprets your speech in English. This happens despite the fact that the last message you wrote using this app to the same contact on your iPhone was in Japanese.  Normally, the watch interprets speech in the language of the last used keyboard for a specific contact in Apple's Message app. Therefore, in order to get the Apple Watch to interpret your speech in the correct language again, you must go back to your iPhone and select the standard Apple keyboard for the contact in the Message app. This is very inconvenient.  This is the only reason I rate this app with only three stars. If you don't have an Apple Watch, then this app is great.

This game has become exclusively about who is willing to pour money into the game versus the game used to be about work and reward as well as team comradery. They are always the strongest and capable of rushing 70-80% of their fellow players. I really wish everything in this game -as far as ranking /needs/ and building strength did not revolve around paying for 3/4 of it. At this point over 1/2 of 20 leagues I played with have already abandoned their castles and quit playing all together. For the average person looking for a way to relax and enjoy a game -I wouldn‚Äôt recommend SF, but if you are above average economically with a competitive trait and have money to burn-then I would recommend this game. Well, Lost is my favorite tv show of all time, and this game is basically Lost + zombies. I can't believe how cheap it is. I throw so much money at these BS games that just kill time -- I would be willing to spend a decent amount of money on an expansion or console version (although it‚Äôd essentially be Dead Island - I just really love this game.)   I was starting to think this game was getting repetitive until I prematurely tried to disarm the center island tesla, then I realized I should just go work on the third (NE in my case) island first. And HOLY MOLY the third island was like a whole new game entirely. So many more bases, a hidden little oasis through a tunnel of trees, with actual decorations in the houses that you can take. Crazy amounts of zombies, but crystal transformers at every transit location.   I love this game and cannot believe it isn't more popular.   Anyways -- the few cons I've noticed (that don't make the game unplayable at all) :   Zombies get stuck in walls, a lot of the dig sites don't work, sometimes auto aim doesn't seem to work but I suppose that could be user error, there could be different enemies or some more change of scenery.   Anyways -- spend the three dollars and try it out. It's a hidden gem of the App Store. I‚Äôd legit pay a good $30-40 or so on a PS4 version.

Lovely paper art style with relaxing music backdrop a game where milliseconds make the difference between success and horrible jet pack crash. And you will crash. Repeatedly. Because gravity, momentum, and the frailness of the human body are your greatest adversaries, not to mention the how off-balance you are. The simple two-thumb controls are as intuitive as your pack is unwieldy, and the game pushes you to fly through a series of timed challenges that steadily but fairly increase in difficulty through the campaign. After each failure, you can retry instantly, and the cycle of repeated attempts lulls you into a zen-like state as you slowly improve. This is a game that is difficult to learn and perhaps impossible to master, but easy to keep playing after each failure, because you know you need just one more chance. Or two. Or fifty.

This little gem has slipped down a slope of controversial loss of support. People see the beauty in it and cry about how they want more and since they aren't getting it, they berate this great game. Does it have flaws? Sure. Is it still boldly beautiful? Absolutely.   But here's the thing, wanna know why there's lack of bug fixing? Because as the developers were working on finishing it, the terror attacks in Paris of late 2015 occurred and affected this studios' people. That's right, put two and two together and you'll realize from their forum posts that they didn't have the capabilities to overcome what happened right after the first few patches of this game.  Are the controls tight? Sometimes a little too tight. They need to include a walk through because there are features of the game with no instruction. Like: you have to go back to town and talk to your Captain to change party members. But the end of this game has a trailer for what they hoped would be the rest of the story. And it leaves me thirsty for more. I'd say to people who want to still try it, know you're going in on a game that had a tragic loss regarding its development. Post to their forums and let them know what you like and don't like. But for all the work that was put into it, I'll give them 4 stars for what could have been the greatest Indy rpg on the App Store.

As an app publisher myself I was completely mystified why anyone would publish a game of this caliber and then completely abandon it without so much as a bug fix update for over a year. Even if it didn‚Äôt sell well, a bug-fix for something as egregious as the assault bug would have been a minimal common courtesy for those who did purchase the game I order to make it playable for them. I‚Äôm rating it 4 stars instead of 5 mostly because while the game itself is excellent, I can‚Äôt rate it 5 stars given the lack of service the publisher has shown so far. This is perfect for pulling diagrams and tables out of high yield review texts for classnotes without maintaining the in-book design.  I scanned a table and was able to make original looking notes in a concept map format from all the info within a minute.  Realize that this is definitely meant to do that, not much more.  The template can only be applied post editing, so you cant write on the paper background you want it in.  Only one pen option which you can change the style of in the post editing template area, but not in active editing.  The pen absolutely needs to have a smaller line width option - 3 available and to really use this practically, the narrowest setting is where I'd have a highlighter set to.  The app is great for not getting distracted and for what it is.  A few minor tweaks would make it excellent, in my opinion.

Carbo makes pretty good scans, but it‚Äôs crippled by the lack of a viable export option. Users need to be able to select multiple scans and export them to PDF or other file formats. Until that happens, save your money and consider this unusable for most purposes.

It's hard to believe, really. Even after all this time, L&L still cannot improve the Scrivener sync process. The people behind Scrivener are clearly intelligent. One look at the macOS version especially, and it's plain to see the great minds behind the design. Which is why this whole pathetic syncing process baffles me.  Like everyone, I was thrilled to see the iOS version finally released about 3 years ago, even though the UI left a lot to be desired. Still, we could now take our writing on the road, and that was huge. It seemed like a dream come true... until we actually started trying to sync our documents. Holy moly, what a mess! Complaints poured in, and rightfully so. The developers had completely dropped the ball.  It was so bad, I abandoned Scrivener in favor of Ulysses. I set up exactly the same folder structure in Ulysses that I had created in Scrivener, and every single change on either macOS or iOS updated instantly ‚Äî instantly, right before my eyes, without me having to do anything. You can literally hold your iPhone or iPad up beside your MacBook screen, edit a file on either device, and within a couple of seconds, your edits will automatically appear on the other device, even with the projects open! The folks at L&L kept saying their project / folder layout was too complex to make syncing work like that. Obviously that's not true.  So today I decided to update all my devices to the latest version of Scrivener and give it another go. Surely by now all those silly problems would have been resolved. Well, uh, they haven't. The sync process is literally agonizing to watch. First of all, nothing syncs automatically. Seriously?? But even after manually initiating a sync, the nightmare has only begun. You are forced to close the app. Yes, close the app so the project can sync. But the fun doesn't end there. To import your changes onto your other device, you have to, you guessed it ‚Äî close the app on that device, too. What is this, 1998?  Words cannot describe how much I love Scrivener on the Mac, and how much I want to use it as my only source for writing books. But there is no way on God's green earth that I'm going to trust my manuscripts to such an outdated, clunky process!  Not. A. Bloody. Chance!  I guess I'll check back in a year or so and see if Scrivener's syncing process has been dragged out of the dark ages and turned into something that just works without me even having to think about it... like all my other apps already do. But I just noticed that Scrivener on iOS has not been updated in over a year, so I'm not going to hold my breath.

I played this game for 3+ years. I mostly enjoyed it, although it irked me that the honeybees are enemies who get in the gardener‚Äôs way, to the point that I sometimes had to remove them. The challenges are a bit repetitive: grow flower until they explode, ‚Äúpick‚Äù bouquets of flowers, destroy weeds; the only interesting part is the changing layout for each level, and dealing with enemies like snails, crows, honeybees, and gophers. About a year into the game, it failed. I don‚Äôt remember if the screen locked up, or what happened, but I had to delete it and reinstall it. All my progress up the map was lost. So I started over. This time I decided to complete each level to three stars before moving on. Some levels took more than a month to complete three stars. I took great satisfaction in reviewing my unbroken streak of three stars across the map, up to Level 269. Then, last week the map disappeared. I sent a ticket to support. I got a canned response. Following the instructions on the response, I created a user account and searched the discussions on the King Community boards. Sure enough, there was a thread on missing maps, with a screenshot identical to my game view. Dated 10 months ago, in December 2018. Several posts from January and February showed that the problem was never even acknowledged, let alone addressed. So I sent a second email to support. Got the same canned response as before. Losing the map drops my interest in the game to zero. The lack of support makes me question any investment of time in a King game. I have deleted Blossom Blast Saga and will not be back.

Updated update: *still* a cool idea. Dark UI theme is very much appreciated, as are standard iOS gestures for drawing and zooming. Now: copy/paste? Please? It is the one missing function that keeps me from using this app more than once every few months.   Update: MIDI export: yay! All the other stuff: still want, especially copy/paste, dark UI, and regular iOS scrolling and drawing gestures. Also, there seems to be an annoying lag with the current two-finger drawing: I lift my left thumb but if I try to scroll too quickly with my right, I end up with a stack of notes that have to be erased.    Thanks for listening to your users!  ---  I'm giving this app four stars because I like the idea so much and because even though it is missing some fairly basic functionality it is already extremely flexible in the variety of musical ideas you can take down. I was not even sure anyone had made a simple piano roll music editing app when I went looking for one, but here it is, brand new!  So it is a piano roll-style music writing app that comes without a hugely complex DAW attached to it. It can be used for microtonal work at a fairly rough resolution: if you turn off the snap-to-pitch option, it will let you draw notes anywhere between (Western even-tempered 12-tone) pitches that you would like. It is equally flexible with regard to meter: snap-to-time can be turned on or off, and although the roll itself has grid lines for regular measures, you can ignore them entirely.  Without the snap-to functions, you can sketch melody lines freely, but there is little precision if you want to be able to create tones at precise frequencies that are not on the even-tempered scale. I have not been able to find any additional preferences to changes scales for the snap-to values. And so this truly is a sketchpad if precision is important to your music but you are trying to work outside of modern even-tempered Western music.  My main problems with this app are that very basic digital tools are missing. There is no copy/paste on the sketchpad itself, so repeating structures can take some time to fill in. There is no export of any kind: no audio files, not even an image file of the sketch itself. A dark background app theme would be very helpful for those of us who find glaring white backgrounds painful--or even just annoying--to work with.   This app has a lot of potential. Honestly, I could see it becoming into a synth/sampler that created audio stream output. MIDI would be gravy, if challenging to implement.  At the least, my wishes for added options would be something like the following:  Improved editing: copy/paste; the ability to draw straight lines from one arbitrary point to another rather than being restricted to snap-to-pitch; and making the non-standard two finger drawing/zoom function optional while adding the usual iOS gestures for these functions--myself, I find those gestures adequate and those implemented here to be awkward.   Import user samples for custom instruments.  Export and/or record audio into aiff or wav format.  A sine oscillator as one instrument choice--this would give the app and the user some basic synthesizing power.  Audiobus integration that would allow further processing of the audio output.  Great start. Add more stuff! :)

Next to the hundreds of challenges in One More Jump, the nuanced gameplay of One More Bounce or even the novel sling mechanic of One More Line, One More Dash is the simplest: tap to jump from circle to circle, but time each move to avoid the colored barriers travelling around each target. That's it.  Still, the various unlockable color schemes are amazing...clearly made by smart visual designers who know what they're doing. I love toggling the different color schemes depending on my mood, the time of day, etc. Really sharp.  The music is also pitch-perfect. Gets your heart pounding without being distracting.  Ultimately, this is pretty much the perfect game for 2- to 5-minute bursts. Just don't expect terribly deep gameplay.

Timepage provides an incredibly useful feature that can not be found in the native Apple Calendar app, and that‚Äôs the ability to show every ‚Äúall-day‚Äù event when the number of events on a single day is greater than 4.  In Calendar, all day events appear in the top grey bar when in day view, but only the first 4 appear fully. All day events 5 & 6 are cutoff and anything beyond that is difficult to see at a glance. So if you are active with multiple events to juggle, Timepage will be incredibly useful.  The reason why I can‚Äôt rate it higher is because I do not like the subscription model. I‚Äôve been using this for years and have been grandfathered in (for now) but subscription after subscription just becomes very expensive once you add them ALL up.  I fully like the idea of supporting great developers and their useful products but I hope they share the same concern that ALL of our subscription when added together are becoming too expensive to justify, making the subscription model one that will eventually need to fail.

Formulas and Stackables are my favorite filter apps. They can make all the difference in bringing out the nuance, mood and beauty of an image. I use these filters for the majority of my creations, and I, like so many other creatives, have been very, very sad and disappointed that Stackables is no longer being updated and available on the App Store, and that Formulas may follow. There have been many discussions in the mobile photography and art groups on Facebook regarding this as the apps are so widely used and loved. Every teacher of mobile art and photography I know, hundreds of artists, books regarding the subject, and numerous articles, have mentioned and recommended Stackables. With the continued influx of artists in this growing genre of mobile art and photography, both Stackables and Formulas would continue to grow in popularity. I‚Äôve been wondering, can another developer not acquire Stackables and continue to develop it and keep it available? And why is it not worth continuing to develop? These apps are so much a part of my creative output, I‚Äôve even considered no longer downloading IOS updates on my devices in order to insure I can continue to use them!

Gorgeous filters. Gives my images that special pizzazz that I haven‚Äôt been able to get from other filter apps.  I also use Stackables, which I love love love, from the same developer.   I‚Äôm super sad that Stackables is no longer available in the App Store. Rumor is that Formulas is also being discontinued.  Always a sad day when wonderful apps die.

I've played Puzzel Strike off and on for a couple of years.   I have the board game version, and I used to play the Free Web Version while I was on my walking treadmill.  This iOS implementation is very polished.  I was a little worried after readinng the negitive reviews, but I went forward with a buddy and we both bought a copy.  It played smooth as single player (and the puzzle mode is nice), and today we tried it multiplayer.   At first we could not get a custom game started (we'd pick the characters but could not start it or edit the bank), so I posted on the Forum on their website, and within 5 mins (9pm cst) there was a reply from the admin stating the Server was in a "bad state" for iOS and he'd reboot it.   Well he did, and my friend and I did about 4 hours of stable play across the internet (while running Facetime).  Super solid implementation - though with hiccups and growing pains.

Messages that display programmer info (like an empty object showing as "{0}")' no Undo for many actions, and a Custom game mode that doesn't let you choose your bank or start the game. This feels like a Single Player beta. It is in no way finished and doesn't merit the $4 price tag. Keep your money until Sirlin gets their act together.

As mentioned by others, the create account system just doesn't work. And there's no way to contact the developers to alert them to the problem. Which means I won't be spending the $12(!!!!) to unlock the rest of he game. Which, by the way, feels a bit exorbitant for an app that doesn't support pass and play, and since I can't log in, means I can't play with my friends at all. See, if you do the math, $12 * 4 means that you and your friends will pay $48 to play the full game against each other. That's more than the cost of the actual board game.

The sound is pretty bad at most times, with volume levels being wildly uneven, and lackluster, repetitive sound effects. The voice acting is pretty bad for some characters but Eisenhorn and most of the main characters are good. While the character models are beautifully rendered for the main characters, the standard for enemies and others is noticeably lower.The animations for everyone are very jerky, and usually too fast, making it hard to see exactly what happens. All this aside, I still love the game and it‚Äôs totally worth the money.

Plenty of skill and strategy will be needed if you are going to make it through this game, Ellipsis. In this game you will have to navigate, using your finger on the touch-screen, a circle around the level avoiding enemies, traps, and other dangers. You will also be tasked with collecting at least four of the circle objects on the screen, but there is a catch... You see not only do you have to make contact with each of these spots on the screen, but you will have to have precision, otherwise you're not going to be able to collect all the dots inside the circles.   The dots will tell you what your final score will be, and of course the object of any game is you're going to want to catch them all. That being said, if you are a true gamer you're going to want to do speed runs in already conquered levels so that you can unlock an additional star to add to your overall score.  I had the chance to first find out about this game when I went to MomoCon, and the neon colors of the game, and the simplicity of the design drew me in. This is a very polished game, and it has one of the best features in my mind when it comes to games that are going to require you to constantly have your finger on the screen and that is instant pause if your finger leaves the screen. Holy crap, that feature alone is awesome.  The levels are quick, there's infinite tries per level, and if you start really advancing through the game different paths open up that reconnect further down the line, so there's a chance that you can get through the game without having to take on every single level, but trust me when I say, you're going to want to beat every level. Personally the feeling of accomplishment when you finally defeat a level that has thwarted you is unreal.  Alright so lets get a little bit more into the game. This of course is a game in which you are going to be guiding your circle, with the help of your finger, around the screen to specific points, each of these points has small bubbles/circles inside of them, if you just skim the point the bubbles/circles will be released into the level. You can choose not to pursue them, but you will docked at the end of the level. Each time you hit a point a new one appears, so you won't know where all of them are until you've played through the level at least once. As stated before there's always going to be an optional fifth point that will pop up at the same time that the portal shows up. To end the level you have to go through the portal, just make sure that you go between the edges of the portal and not right at the portal, I learned the hard way that you're going to bounce off of the edge and if you're being chased by something nasty, you're probably going to have to replay the level.  There is one more thing I want to say about this game and that is the game map. As you play through the game you get a new area unlocked, and the developers could have just given you linear dots on the screen with a description, but not with this game. It basically feels like you're unlocking a futuristic arcade like world where the area dots form an ever growing constellation. So with that I think you can all tell that this game, in my opinion, is solid and definitely worth your time, especially at a very reasonable price. This game gets a 9.3 out of 10.

You will not regret downloading this game. Find an alliance that is helpful too!

This game is super under-rated‚Äîit‚Äôs great turn-based strategy. If you like Advance Wars, or Warbits, or Fire Emblem, Lost Frontier is totally worth trying out.  The teams are asymmetric too, with some interesting differences between the sides.  I wish the UI was a little clearer about which units were good/bad against which, but that‚Äôs relatively minor.

It‚Äôs a game like Advance War on GBA. Recalled my childhood good summer vacation with friends.  One-stop buy a Full-game, without any in-app purchase or ADs.  Awesome graphic and BGM, included story mode and challenge maps.  iCloud save state restore supported! You can play continue your save stage on iPhone or iPad, switch easily. Don‚Äôt worry for lost save process even you lost your iPhone.   But, I found few little bugs, e.g. enemy hero‚Äôs special power disappeared when I restart the game. Unlimited moves in one round, when I click ‚Äùend turn‚Äù then exit the app from background. And this game had no updates more than 2 years after last update. Even so, it‚Äôs my favorite game on my iPhone.  Looking forward lost frontier 2!

Could someone either open-source this or charge me $20 for a DLC expansion (just more maps, minimal effort). There simply isn‚Äôt anything else with this classic TBS format & perfect iPhone play. I have searched obsessively for a turn based strategy game that incorporated terrain, unit types, capturing & defending space and am really glad I finally found Lost Frontier. It‚Äôs perfectly formatted for an iPhone screen, is easy to pick up and has alot of depth and enjoyable challenges in the campaigns. I don‚Äôt like or play many games, but I do like this one, think it‚Äôs fun and sometimes consumes too much of my time.  Please take the last phrase as a big compliment given my tendency to avoid games.  I think the concept for the game fits very well with the explosion of interest in design mainly due to the influence of HGTV and the pioneer design show of the past that have and had competitive spirits as the root of the show.  I also think the player interface and number of elements a player has input ability to go a long way to make this highly interesting and keeps players engaged.  So kudos to all involved in the birth of the ideas for the game, for the execution and delivery of a quality product, and for tweaks and changes as the product. Continues to evolve.  In-app-purchases and absolutely necessary and the business model chosen by most developers today.  I have no issue at all with supporting that business model and prefer it much more than subscriptions.   Another thing you do well is allow free access to every element in the game, which is not common.  Also, with judicious decisions and the ability to earn them for free, a player can go a long way in this game without spending a penny.  So along with the kudos, I‚Äôd like to pass along some aspects of the game that in my own opinion, should be considered important to future updates.     First, I‚Äôve not found a way to change my identity in the game from USER XXXXXXXXXX to a name of my choosing and basically create a profile other than by logging in through a Facebook account.  I refuse to join Facebook and because I do, I‚Äôm prevented from establishing an identity in the game.  I hope there is another way I have missed to login, because if there isn‚Äôt  I won‚Äôt continue to use the game.  I refuse to have to bow to Facebook to use a piece of software and would like a reply from the developer about this.  In my opinion, the weakest part and it‚Äôs very weak, is the voting. How in the world can a design achieve a 5.0 when the designer uses the same piece of wall art multiple times in a room?  If my designer did that, I‚Äôd fire her/him in a second.  Another thing that gets overlooked in voting, is the hodgepodge of finishes (e.g. dark wood, silver, gold, bronze, light wood, etc.) for things like cocktail table, end table, sofa, chair and ottoman legs that again I‚Äôd fire my designer for putting in my house that frequent in rooms that  receive a 5.0 score.  Finally, 5.0 scores are common for designs that are totally inconsistent with the design instructions that are given and I‚Äôm sure frustrate players as I‚Äôve seen reviews citing that issue.  I don‚Äôt have an answer to this other than dropping the vote altogether, but feel it is such a weak part of the game that serious noodling should be done.  Finally, I have had a problem receiving ‚Äúfree diamonds‚Äù that were earned by making a hotel reservation and staying at the hotel through one of your sponsors who is no longer in your list.  I‚Äôm not sure how to rectify this since the sponsor is no longer in your list.  I hope my comments are helpful.

First, I really enjoy the actual design aspect of the game.  Unfortunately, when scoring the designs, very little, if any consideration is given to the original intent of the design, instead, having voting more of a popularity contest than a true design assignment. This seems to be a complaint across the other reviews for this app I have read. Second, and probably the most frustrating part of entering the room design contests, is purchasing furniture, finishing the room and having the corresponding monies deducted from my account....And then, an error occurs and it deletes my room design, forcing me to start over from scratch. This wouldn‚Äôt be so horrible if it also put the money spent on furniture during that particular room design back into my account...it doesn‚Äôt and you end up losing your money.. They also could use a better way of reviewing and sorting your inventory...a good ‚Äúsort‚Äù feature. Which brings me to my third and biggest complaint;  the lack of response from customer service.  Currently, I have an open e-mail from June 11th, 12 days without any response.  I also make sure I update that email, advising them it remains without response.  I have probably spent over $250, much of which was lost during the frequent technical issues that force a reboot mid-game. It is now mid-September and I am still having the same, unanswered issue. They have closed and deleted the correspondence so I am not able to view or print it.  I have made many requests for hard copy print outs to share with my bank to fight the inaccurate charges. The last correspondence took weeks before I received a reply from a ‚Äúperson‚Äù.  I was the asked to confirm some information...unfortunately, when I wasn‚Äôt able to respond within 48 hours, they closed they email and deleted it from view so I was no longer able to reference the issue for my bank. They need to have a better response system, more timely responses, and to provide their customers, me, with a copy of my purchase history alongside the reboot history so I can compare this and obtain a refund of the incorrectly billed funds. Four months is ridiculous. I‚Äôve since requested all the back copies of my correspondence...they delete them from your sight when they determine to close them, even when, like me, the issue is never resolved. It‚Äôs really too bad these problems are becoming more of an issue...I am looking for a different room design app to replace this.

I've been a huge fan of Orange Pixel since Meganoid hit the AppStore years back, so my review is probably going to be pretty bias (just laying it out there, also of note, I've become a pretty big TBS and Roguelike fan over the last couple years). But, this is definitely up there among the best games that they have put out. I don't know if Heroes of Loot or this, Space Grunts, is my #1 favorite OP game, but they both give up an amazingly spectacular run for it. The controls might take some getting use to, as they're virtual, but resizing is coming in an update and ATM you can place every button wherever you'd like on the screen. Once I played about 3 games, they were perfect. I couldn't imagine playing it any other way. The mix of action and turn-based gameplay is done incredibly well. I really just can not stop gushing about every aspect of the game. The menus are well done, the UI layout/map setup is on point, the graphics are killer (though they may not look it in the AppStore screens, the game looks GREAT in motion - check out some HQ vids!), the roguelike aspect is done perfectly---It's a great game. One that has already (VERY VERY quickly) earned it's spot on my own GOTY list (#2 of 2 ATM [Feb]) - but I wholeheartedly recommend this to roguelike fans itching for the genre to take a turn towards more arcade-based gameplay. =oD  **update**  The new update rocks... thank you for the resizing controls option, the new item and giving each character a level upgrade once they beat the game (having something that sticks with you after making it through that was a great decision...) - and the tweaks. This has very quickly become, not only one of my favorite games of the year, but also one of my favorite roguelikes ever. GET IT!!!!

I am learning French by reading French ebooks, among other things.    I literally cannot imagine how much more difficult it would be to learn French without this app.    It is much more convenient than a regular dictionary because you can cut a word from the ebook/article/whatever, then paste it into the search bar of the app.  That is MUCH faster than using a paper dictionary.    The word is almost always in the dictionary -- with French definitions, usage, verb conjugations, special usages, ..  You can look up a verb from any of its forms.  I.e., you do not need to know the infinitive.  There are a few small gaps, but overall this really sets the standard for a well-designed dictionary app.  I only wish I could find similar apps for other languages.  A VERY good value.

I don't write reviews much but this developer has earned it.  I have played DungeonRaid for probably hundreds of hours definitely more than any other mobile game so when I saw Alex had a new game out I jumped on it.  I have played IKHTD for a few months here and there. It's definitely addicting but it's not quite as satisfying. It does not feel like you have nearly enough agency over your fate due to there being such a wide variety of abilities but only being offered a few. This wasn't a problem with DR since leveling up was much faster and more frequent. I keep wanting to try a *build* only to be given what feels useless abilities over and over. When I do finally get the abilities I want normal the difficulty ramps up so quickly I don't get to enjoy it.  I think the game could of been improved by having equal loss of attack and defense. Losing half of your defense every time causes me to treat defense very oddly and not invest in it much. I also think that picking up hearts should count towards events even if your health is full.  IKHTD is worth picking up but if you are here because of DR don't expect quite as satisfying experience. Great job Alex I'll be watching what you do next.

Like the game, there are cool puzzles and like this series. However there is something wrong with the HOPs. There are always a few items that need other items to be changed/worked with using an item in the HOP list. For example a necklace may need to be created using beads that are randomly placed around the HOP screen. U have to move each bead to a certain area of the necklace in order for it to be accepted.  It never failed that I would have to try several times to get the bead to be registered. I would have to reselect the bead a bunch of times and move it to different  parts of the necklace before it would accept that bead and add it to the necklace.  This is very frustrating since u don't know exactly where on the necklace should be dropping it so u just have to try a bunch of times in different sections.  If the item you are trying to drop or the item that it is being dragged to are different sizes, then you have to try a bunch of times to get it in the correct place. This also happened if using items that you already found. You select them from the row of items and drag it up to the HOP screen several times in different places before it would register. The game would be awesome if this bug was fixed.

To be honest if you never changed it I would still play everyday. It would be nice though!  Fantastic game 5/5  *UPDATED REVIEW BELOW*  Wow, this game hasn‚Äôt left my phone since I downloaded it. And that‚Äôs saying a lot because I get bored of games really quickly. You would think there‚Äôs not much to do, but that‚Äôs the beauty of it; you are perfecting the art of falling in a way that hasn‚Äôt been done before!  Reaction time, patience, and a few minutes are the ingredients for a good time in Downwell. But there‚Äôs nothing stopping you from playing it like a slow paced Mario level!  With the characters, upgrades, shop items, and pallete options, this game can be played in countless ways! Amazing!!!!!!  Oh and the only thing I would have added has been added just recently! iPhone X support!

I‚Äôve had this game for longer than I‚Äôve ever kept any game downloaded for, probably all games on my iPhone combined for that matter. After years of playing I finally made it to the last boss. Not because it‚Äôs too hard, it‚Äôs not, it‚Äôs fair with its snappy and crisp, ultra responsive controls that make every mistake your fault and your fault alone. I‚Äôve never play an iOS game that performed better and had 0 input lag like Downwell does. It‚Äôs genuinely designed to keep you playing and coming back to enjoy another round and attempt to find out what is at the bottom of the well, if anything at all. The upgrades don‚Äôt carry with you at death, you amass them every time you reach a new level/depth each run through. The color palette swap was a HUGE part in keeping me playing and engaged as the more colors you unlock, the more complex and varied the next one becomes. besides the incredible gameplay of course lol It rewards you for playing and doesn‚Äôt lock anything away behind progression that could hinder you in jumping down the well for the first time and beating the game. But I promise, you won‚Äôt. Seriously, you won‚Äôt lol it‚Äôs hard. But hard in an incredible way, not artificial to pad length. Only thing locked is visual perks that change the aesthetic and also different play styles. which can change gameplay dramatically if you want a new way to play or challenge to unravel. And the gunboots. I could talk about them forever. So many different kinds. Although my only advice or WANT would be for the devs to include a DLC pack of MORE gun variations in the future. The game is perfect the way it is but as an option to enhance and switch up a game I‚Äôve played and sunk prolly 500-700 hours into over the years, I‚Äôd love MORE GUN MODS. I‚Äôd pay double maybe triple what i payed for the game originally for the option to load the game with even more crazy guns to find when descending down the well. It would give a boost of content and happiness to an already incredible game, and base of players that have been itching for an update to a game that they love so much. I even love the game so deeply it has become the only game I‚Äôve ever bought cross-platform other than Stardew Valley and even ended up enjoying the game even more on my Switch. This is a mobile game at heart and it‚Äôs a mobile game that is worth $15-$20, hands down, it‚Äôs that good. I‚Äôve never seen it priced above $3 dollars ever. I really think it‚Äôs one of the most underrated and under appreciated games of all time. And just one of the best games of all time for that matter. Stylized with incredible use of retro graphics with modern effects that give it a gorgeous look and feel, and controls so responsive I couldn‚Äôt believe that I had never noticed another game that matched its precision. I love this game, truly I do. I hope someone that‚Äôs on the fence on wether they wanna spend a couple bucks on a game on their iPhone reads this and is persuaded because it‚Äôs MORE than worth it for the price they‚Äôre asking. They‚Äôre Essentially giving it away for free if you ask me. I want Downwell to get more praise and more attention and more downloads for the fun it‚Äôs extended to me. It and it‚Äôs developers deserve so much more praise; it‚Äôs a simple concept flipped on its boots and man does it really pull off what a game is supposed to be at its core, fun. Extremely fun.

Will update stars with dev feedback, seems like only bad reviews get attention.  I love Rolling Sky. Been with it the whole journey, 100% on E-Labyrinth, the stuff. Been with it since the levels were identified with Roman numerals. Loving Faster and all of that stuff. Few problems and recommendations: 1) COSTS WAY TOO MUCH! Free to download. Too much spending money to fully experience. I payed the full $2 for unlimited balls and no ads, but I‚Äôd like to see something new. For example, unlimited balls by default. Pay $1 to remove ads. Maybe checkpoints use more hearts as you use them more, maxing out at 3 hearts? Maybe for every level you beat at Sky level or harder (cause I know people would spam Cloud if on any level) you get free hearts (like 2 star or somethig like that) even if you‚Äôve beaten it before, instead of watching ads on the fly? Watching ads makes it too easy. Maybe for levels at Alone Remix or harder you get a super heart for each time you beat it, even if you beat it before? That would encourage me to take my 88% to 100% and GET GOOD at the game, which was clearly made to help you progress and get better through harder levels. 2) Ads currently not working for me when connected to internet, but that might just be my internet. 3) Maybe a custom level editor? I love playing Rolling Sky, but I would LOVE to be able to make my own levels and play them. The ability to insert your own soundtracks by choosing them in your preffered music app (changeable in game) and add songs like adding music to a playlist, the ability to use any blocks you wish, the ability to make multiple changeable backgrounds, the ability to insert chosen images as backgrounds, the ability to create multiple heights on the level like in Happy Birthday, the ability to name, save, and publish levels, and more would be the best thing that could happen to this game. 4) An Original Levels collection A seperate collection for the eleven original levels. Oh, and please add the OG Forest back.  Oh, and what happened to Alan Walker (actually K-391‚Äôs) Ignite? Really want to play that again. 37% and then lost it.  Also, trial tickets for new AW/Marshmello levels should always be available, like with key-based levels (but I can see doing the ‚Äútry again later‚Äù thing as a way to get people to stop spamming and actually try)  Please read this, Cheetah. I love Rolling Sky, and I love seeing new things.

I'm going to try and get my money back, having been tricked into buying this thing. This thing seems to have been designed by an AI with the barest understanding of what constitutes a game. Either that or it was a level one exercise in graphics programming at a coding institute in an East Asian country. It really is simply a few basic programming elements slapped haphazardly together ‚Ä¶ and that's it.  Basically you tap left and right to guide a first-person perspective "runner" down platforms in a 3D monochrome maze as an 8-bit theme, around five notes booping up and down a major scale, loops in the background and a voice narrates nonsense phrases: "Your shoes are shiny. Now is not the time for your inner fight. I am not with you." Like that. The eye-hurting monochrome colors change randomly. There are a few random objects floating in space between the platforms: woman heads, Ben Franklin heads, arms, buildings. They serve no purpose. The screen glitches randomly. Sometimes your runner runs into a cube that chimes and changes the monochrome background once more. If you fall off the platform you start over. As you progress down the maze the runner's speed increases, and the runner's base starting speed also increases a little each time you are "killed" and restart, unless you force quit the game and restart the app entirely to bring your runner back to the beginning base speed ‚Ä¶ so probably the game designers gain some advantage every time a player logs out of Game Center and logs back in again, maybe something involving ranking. Anyhow, there are no clues to the mazes, and most of the challenge of running through them involves poor control response or being visually unable to see what's happening, either by having the screen blocked by glitches or by being blinded by a particularly bright monochrome background, lime on canary, for example, or orange against tangerine. Finishing a level brings up a new one that's slightly different from the last, for no particular reason, as there is no storyline, no plot, no interaction other than tapping left and right and hoping the runner responds, and the random objects don't change, they just cycle.  Seriously, this is a coding exercise someone decided to sell as an overpriced app. Imagine you were demonstrating 3D technology for the first time, and you just looped visuals of a first-person perspective going over a set of ramps, turning left and right around an Atari 2600 representation of a city comprising nine office blocks, three woman heads, a Ben Franklin head and seven up-stretched arms. To demonstrate voice synthesis you program in some phrases from a phrase book: "Your shoes are shiny. The city is alive tonight." Because you're limited to 8-bit color for this 101 class exercise you choose monochromes of lime green against emerald green. And that's it.  But to drum up excitement you shell out one eighth of a Bitcoin to bored Russian youths on whatever the current version of Hansa Market is to buy 250 good reviews from them. And there you have the game's gameplay and business model. ‚Ä¶Enjoy?  Seriously, don't buy this thing. Just don't. Get a level-1 programming book and code in the first exercise of the first page of the first chapter into Eclipse yourself and you will get pretty much the same result, for cheaper, and you'll have learned a new skill to boot. But don't reward the lazy failing student who cribbed this from a beginner's guide to 8-bit color and 3D vector plane graphics.

This is just a port of a PSP graphic update to a beloved game boy game that has aged very very poorly. While the polygonal 3-D graphics are snazzy, and the music as awesome as ever, the gameplay and storyline of this game were really never very engaging.....or fun to begin with.  Control wise, if you have an MFI controller, then it plays perfectly but who cares when you‚Äôll be endlessly grinding against flat uninteresting monsters in order to accomplish forgettable fetch quests thrown at you by cardboard characters in a mellow dramatic, convoluted ‚Äústory‚Äù so contrived and so ham fisted that it makes daytime soap operas feel like Shakespeare by comparison?  The game is riddled with game ending, unsolvable ‚Äúpuzzles‚Äù that involve doing asinine, ridiculously cryptic tasks like: walking around two trees in a the shape of a figure 8 until a secret door opens.....at some random, undisclosed place in the monotonous, one dimensional woods, that look like all the other woods. Without a walkthrough the game is virtually unbeatable.  With the look and sound being as good as it is, if this game were a completely reimagined (True Remake) of Final Fantasy Adventure then I think they could justify the relatively steep price.... but as it is? This game is just not worth the money or the time. The original was considered good in its time, for a game boy game (that people couldn‚Äôt beat even back then) but by todays standards your better off playing so many other games.

I generally like the user experience. But one thing that bothers me is that if you move on to the next task before the time runs out on the current task, then the current tasks won‚Äôt be marked as ‚Äúcompleted‚Äù.  So if you give yourself 15 minutes to eat breakfast, but finish eating in just 10 minutes, then you have to sit around and do nothing for 5 minutes if you want the ‚Äúeat breakfast‚Äù task to be marked as complete.  If you skip ahead to the next task before the time is up, it doesn‚Äôt get marked as competed. So weird!  You also don‚Äôt have an option of completing tasks out of order.  So if your next task is ‚Äútake a shower‚Äù but your partner is using the bathroom, you can‚Äôt just move on to another task and come back to the current one later.  The Routinist app has really figured out all these little details. But their UI isn‚Äôt very good. I think the Morning Routine app developers should try to duplicate all of Routinist‚Äôs features, but keep the good UI that Morning Routine has. That would make a truly killer app.

I love everything about this game, like the story and characters, like the gameplay and difficulty, I‚Äôve unlocked master on every single song except for the last one in stage 4. I love this game, but most of the songs have become boring after playing them all the time. I don‚Äôt have the money to constantly buy the new packs, and I thought this new Daily Song system sounded awesome! I get to play new songs all the time now! I usually only play a little each day, so it‚Äôll be great for me, right?  Oh, so wrong.  You see, you get five chances every day. Firstly, the song you get is random. You don‚Äôt have any control over what song you play. That wouldn‚Äôt be so bad, even though you have to watch an ad beforehand, if it weren‚Äôt for the second problem. You don‚Äôt even get to choose the difficulty. WHY?! What is there to gain by preventing your players from choosing the diff? It says a ‚Äúrandom difficulty‚Äù, but I got Whisper, the easiest one, all five times. As an experienced player, it was so boring I quit every time trying to get ONE harder song, and never did. Also, if it is truly random, imagine the opposite problem. A new player keeps getting hard songs, gets intimidated and never buys any of them. Or worse, they never play again.  I‚Äôd like to say I appreciate the IDEA. I think a daily song is great, and hey, if I like a map enough I might just consider buying it. But as it stands, being unable to see what I‚Äôm buying makes me very apprehensive, and this new Daily Song system does not alleviate my worries in the slightest.

The review by GoodGuyAvetis is right. It seems that the dividing line separating the left and right buttons isn't centered on my iphone 6. Therefore tapping right makes my ninja go left sometimes. Actually it does that a lot (going left instead of right). eg, instead of ‚¨ÖÔ∏è  |  ‚û°Ô∏è it feels like  ‚¨ÖÔ∏è    |‚û°Ô∏è As you can see there's not much tapping area for right button. If you tap a little to the left of right button, you'll go left.   I have to stretch out my thumb and position it more towards the center of the screen in order to be certain my ninja guy will go right when I tap right otherwise it's a crapshoot (he'll inexplicably go left and get killed). It's awkward and so uncomfortable, my thumb reverts back to a more natural position if I forget about it during gameplay. As a result, I keep dying over the lamest sht like going in the wrong direction.   I can't say if this is a problem on other devices with differing screen sizes because idk. I just know it's a problem when I play on my iphone 6. That's why I don't enjoy playing this game because it's so frustrating. It ruins the whole thing. Do I regret buying this game? Hell yeah I do. Therefore I cant recommend it if you have a device with a similar sized screen. (Assuming that's the problem).   Why can't you developers just shift the perimeters for both left and right buttons just a little more to the left? Then the dividing line would shift a little left and become more centered resulting in more tapping area for the right button.   To be honest, I don't have much confidence they'll even look into it seeing how they infrequently update their games and their tendency to just stop updating altogether after barely a year since release. I hope I'm wrong though.

Many people wonder whether they should get AudioBus or AUM.   I‚Äôve used Audiobus since it‚Äôs first version so to me that answer was clear once I came back to iOS music production: AudioBus 3.   That being said there‚Äôs so much talk about AUM going around so I HAD to get it eventually. I must say I wouldn‚Äôt ‚Äúchoose‚Äù between one anymore.   Both are great and I would certainly recommend any: AUM however is far more intuitive and had a sleeker UI.   One thing I love about AUM is it‚Äôs AUv3 handling; the resizing of windows is amazing and really lets you take advantage of the small iPhone‚Äôs screen. You can have several apps at once displayed on a small tiny screen which I find amazing.   That being said, this is the only reason I wrote a review:  There‚Äôs another kid in town who does this even SLIGHTLY better than AUM, and that is ApeMatrix. I have the three and tbh I choose a different one depending on what I need. Often times I even combine them into my workflow.   However, ApeMatrix does ONE thing better than AUM in AUv3 territory and I beg AUM to take note and implement the same behavior as it really would make the app quite better:  ApeMatrix will let you resize AUv3 plugins just like AUM does, but the huge advantage to ApeMatrix is that these AUv3 modules remember their position on screen even after being closed. Unfortunately AUM does not do this; this means everytime you open multiple AUm3 instances you have to organize them on your screen whereas on ApeMatrix you do that once and it‚Äôs set for the whole project. This allows ApeMatrix to work better as a AUv3 host as I can simply use this app in conjunction with my midi keyboard and pads to trigger opening such plugins whenever I need to have them on sight.   The second detail is that double clicking on the ‚Äúedge‚Äù of a plugin‚Äôs window in ApeMatrix automatically makes it full screen: AUM does the same but if you double click again it RESETS its UI, as opposed to ApeMatrix which preserves the ‚Äúminimized UI‚Äù and leads you back to it once you double click on the edge again.   This is also amazing and should be implemented in AUM as it allows for one to have multiple ‚Äúmini AUv3‚Äù plugins which you can maximize to have full control of through the screen only when needed.   These are two small requests that could potentially make AUM even better.  Otherwise, this is a great app and a friendlier  version of AudioBus, also sleeker (you‚Äôll probably need both in the long run tho, and also ApeMatrix. Best 3 mixers out there).

I wish more VR games supported mfi controllers. It blows me away that they don‚Äôt. It‚Äôs a shame the Google Cardboard is such a profoundly limiting platform; even the viewing angle suffers. With that said, it is an excellent game tarnished by some rather serious design flaws.   A huge part of the fun for a game like this is PILOTING a space ship and yet we can‚Äôt do this here. Instead, we hardly more than float through a dog fight while we shoot the baddies around us. I realize that this is an accommodation to the Cardboard platform but I really wish they had included a way to accelerate when using a game pad. Immersion suffers significantly because of it. Additionally, running out of ammo is just a stupid way to end a game.  Ultimately, the game offers an exciting taste of what the future of iOS gaming holds‚Äîbut just a taste.

I enjoyed playing Eclipse.  It has an excellent length, good graphics, and some interesting puzzles.  On the other hand, it can be really annoying.  My biggest annoyance is the absence of a map.   There is no way to determine what is next and no way to transport to the next place.  As a result, I have spent endless amounts of time wandering aimlessly.  The hint button might has well have been absent since the only thing it tells you is "you can't do anything here."  While the strategy guide is excellent, you have to restart the game every time you use it. (And Big Fish needs to stop dumping multiple ads into its web site!) Overall, I'd give it a 3-star rating.
