I‚Äôve played all the free games so finally tried this paid game. While I think the game is worth the small cost, it‚Äôs somewhat disappointing.   The logic puzzles in ‚Äúhotel‚Äù seem simpler and more straightforward than in the free games. What‚Äôs frustrating is how much the ordering of events is relevant to getting a top score. The result is that beating the game involves a lot of rote repetition to order your actions optimally. This makes the game last longer but at a cost of tedium, particularly because the ordering is arbitrary and not clued in any way. In particular there‚Äôs at least one instance (2nd guest meal if done in correct order) where an item is required twice in order to get a perfect score - but one of the two actions makes the item unusable. So those two actions have to be done twice, for no reason other than arbitrary choice. (If the item remaine available to be picked up again, ordering wouldn‚Äôt matter.)

Terrifying. Necessary. It‚Äôs probably easier than you think. Getting out of flow state is my problem, weirdly enough. Once I start writing, I get in such a compulsive state of flow, I can‚Äôt make myself stop typing even when I want to. I use this to train myself by letting the writing fade. It‚Äôs a backwards way to use it, but it took that problem I had and neutralized it down to ...what is now, in terms of writing ... not my issue, but my edge.   But if you want to be in flow-state, just do this until you‚Äôre no longer monitoring yourself, let anything come out, and don‚Äôt feel the need to read it again. It‚Äôs a good way to purge mental clutter, to learn things you didn‚Äôt know you thought about, to get some weird poetic dream-like writing (if you‚Äôre into that) or just to see what happens. Sometimes I like to write the best thing I‚Äôve ever written, and let it almost disappear. Don‚Äôt do that though....it‚Äôs probably not healthy lol. üòè  To do this without this app (sorry developers) use a pad and pen and try not to let the pen leave the page... or stop moving, even if you are just scribbling for a minute, it‚Äôs the same effect minus the panic attacks from the documents disappearing. One word to describe this game - outstanding. This is my first Glitch game and if they are all this well made, I am excited to play all the rest! The graphics are great, gameplay is smooth, puzzles are very challenging, yet fun, and the game is just a super fun game. I‚Äôve been playing for 3 hours straight and I‚Äôm not even close to being finished. If you are looking for a fun and challenging point and click, escape type game with good puzzles, give this game a try. You will totally LOVE it.  Edit: I just played A Short Tale AGAIN and it was just as fun as the first time I played it. I absolutely love this cute game.

A Short Tale is the 6th Glitch Game that I have played, and it is one of their best. The puzzles were a nice balance between clever and fiendish, with a few being maybe a little too close to fiendish. (I am looking at you Magic 8 Ball!) I liked the change in tone from the darker elements of Forever Lost, as this game is one that I would let my younger kids try out. I also thought the smaller environment within one room was a nice change of pace as it meant that you did not have to travel far to investigate a new clue or to search for the next clue. Looking forward to more offerings from Glitch.

This game is a puzzle game in which you struggle to not enjoy the art so you don't explode from incompetence.  Pros:  The art is really good at being simple, recognizable, and humorous. (If you get to look at it for more than the split second it allows) The animation is simple and effective (which you won't notice because you are busy looking at the cars) There is a surprising array of cars on display. From the VW party bus to the Bugatti, the sprites in this game do an accurate depiction of famous vehicles.   Cons: If you struggle with pattern recognition you will not enjoy this game. Tight time limits make finding the cars on this ever changing board a challenge. Not to mention you can't even enjoy your robot punching a huge plant-crab-fish-Dino in the eye :( Customizing your robot does not change the cars on the board or abilities you use. You will skip Cutscenes, especially the combining one in every level.  This game is worth the .99 it asks for, however it probably will not keep you for very long.

Another example of "Graphics before Gameplay". While the game looks nice and definitely advanced in graphics (somewhat). Gameplay is VERY clunky. You must support a series of "Power-Stations" with an Agent, to support you must go to the station yourself and do whatever objectives asked. That's pretty much all you do. You will eventually get more Agents, however, THEY'RE COMPLETELY USELESS unless you start playing on them. So you find yourself with sticking to one agent only and upgrading him/her only. There are numerous bugs and glitches in the game. Invisible walls in the air, untouchable enemies, and much more. Some of these bugs (usually graphical ones) can completely ruin your game (Character frozen in jump sequence, controls literally died and can't move or turn, to name a few.). It did one thing right, it brought console gaming to mobile, indeed.

The concept behind the game is cool, though there is plenty of room for improvement. Fighting chains of enemies seem a little choppy because the character completely stops and stands rather than flowing smoothly to attack the next enemy. The gameplay has quite a few bugs that ruin the experience. These are a handful I've run into:  1. The dashing ability seems to remain usable until the second character is unlocked.  2. Jumping from a high place results in the character getting stuck floating forward with complete loss of control instead of landing on the platform. Only getting attacked by an enemy seems to return the character back to normal. Running off the platform is the only way to avoid this.  3. Failing challenges while in mid-air causes character to float and show the fail animation  4. Attempting to restart the game while falling doesn't work at times  5. Targeting certain enemies is occasionally impossible unless you target and attack a different enemy first  6. Initial infection rate of an area is always the same as the percent you finish the area with regardless of what it initially had  7. After the tumors start showing up on the power stations, there have been a few soldier enemies that randomly appear and can't be killed  8. Buying turrets doesn't appear to make them appear unless it's during a mission  9. Enemies can be pushed through tumors while attacked  10. Unable to scroll through skill description to see the cost of each upgrade  11. Attacking a jumping enemy can cause the camera to be stuck facing up  12. Attacking near a ledge can cause character to get stuck and unresponsive instead of falling off  13. Characters that are injured can still be selected before they are healed

SPOILERS...  This entire chapter is based around an army-management minigame, building up to a battle at the end.  Now here‚Äôs the big spoiler.  WINNING OR LOSING MAKES NO DIFFERENCE.  If you win, you will get cheated of your victory by your plot-armored nemesis. If you lose, you will survive due to your own plot armor. Whatever happens, your friends will be all right and your kingdom will be overrun by demons.  In fact, losing may be BETTER. You get to screw up the minigame as badly as you like, and you‚Äôll get a brainwashed friend back. In order to win, you have to kill them. If you lose, the only named NPC who dies is a gruff general who barely appears in The Lost Heir 3 anyway. The only real reason to win is bragging rights.  I assume the author responded to feedback that failing TLH1‚Äôs boss battle had far too harsh drawbacks by lowering the consequences for losing, but having an arguably NEGATIVE outcome for winning is bewildering.   END SPOILERS  I recommend just focusing on building up your character for TLH3, because that‚Äôs where the stat checks become truly brutal. Again, I recommend physical classes because, if you focused on Magic alone, getting a good ending will be much harder there.

I have more criticism than praise for this game, but it's still a positive rating because it has a certain appealing charm to its aesthetics.   The best thing about the design is the branching and minor backtracking in the level design that makes it interesting to explore.  Levels are fun to explore for secrets but the player view is too limited to see hazards that should be visible. The level design doesn't take visibility into account. You often can't tell if dropping into a lower area is safe or if there are spikes. When you have to leap across a pit, you can't see the other side and judge distance. Pull the camera back a little so players can see more. Also maybe allow players to drag the view a limited distance from the avatar to see farther.  Constant pop ups to watch ads for game credits in mid game is annoying. Should limit ads to reasonable break points in gameplay. Also, should not allow watching ads to earn upgrades without playing the game because it cheapens the feel of earning upgrades through gameplay.   Combat is dull button mashing. Player lacks options in combat so every fight feels the same.  Getting stun locked is death and feels lame. There's nothing you can do to win if you're stunned. Player needs ability to break stun. Stun lock by spikes is especially annoying since you're stuck until you die so it's worse than instant death.   Some enemies can shoot from inside walls, which feels cheap since you can't fight back, and feels like careless design.   Gear upgrade system is boring, since every item for each equipment slot must be bought in order and each is just a slightly stronger version of the previous. It's not any different from just adding more points into a stat.   Art style and music are very nice. Animations and sound effects lack energy.

Then after that lobotomy you might play for an hour or two then find out it didn‚Äôt save anything and you need to do the whole intro again.  Also don‚Äôt bother with the challenges, as soon as an enemy spawns the game harasses you with one of its constant pop ups begging you to watch a video while you get shanked in the background.  I gladly support games with ad clicks and purchases but not when they constantly interrupt the actual game with greedy panhandling.

This game is a lot of fun. I‚Äôve played the other major game dev games like the ones from Kairosoft and Greenheart Games. There are some aspects of this that are great, like the size and multiple teams. It‚Äôs a completely enjoyable game to play. But...  There are a few things that the other games do better. Having access to all genres and game types from the get go is nice, but not being able to see what combinations are best makes innovation nearly impossible, and without any benefit. There‚Äôs nothing to be gained by experimenting with different combinations of type, genre, platform, age group, etc. because it doesn‚Äôt save what you‚Äôve learned so far. The two other games above have a system to learn from the games you‚Äôve made so that you can see what combinations work best and improve in the future. There‚Äôs seemingly no rhyme or reason to why games succeed or fail, and it‚Äôs impossible to figure it out. The only option is to look for guides and lists that have recommendations for good combinations and just repeat the same dozen that I know work. Innovation is integral in the game development industry, and this has none of that.

So you beat them and then what? Nothing.   There's a pretty cool foundation here but you need something to get the player interested in playing the game and trying to play well. From what I can tell I can pretty much start a level, wait for it to expire then play the bonus round for my 150-1000 flomboys over and over although with no advancement. Like I said, it all seems pointless.

UNBELIEVABLY short, even at the sale price. Shame, because the game, what there was of it was great.  Buying BF games is like gambling.  Be prepared to lose your money.  Long time customers are probably familiar with their abysmal customer "service".  A new low for me was the latest Dark Dimensions: Homecoming.  There were problems with the game.  Big surprise, right?  What was new was that instead of their usual do nothing, deny the problem, or blame the customer, they did somethings different.  They did the right thing and updated the app....NOT.  Actually, they did fix the app.  The problem is that instead of issuing it as an update for those of us who had paid the broken app, they released the fixed version as a SEPARATE app. That way, they get rid of those pesky negative reviews so they can attract new buyers while completely screwing over the old buyers.  They gave it a shiny new release date and 1.0 version number but the old broken app is still right there in the App Store.  Also, this week, I discovered that the old buy once play forever....NOT... problem of the supposed past still exists.  I went to open a game I had bought a while ago and it will not work on iOS 8 or newer.  I never played this game.  I bought a bunch of games during the last big sale.  Can't get a refund because it's been over six months (from Apple, who have been great about giving BF refunds versus BF who not only never refunds, but makes you jump through stupid hoops with the promise of a refund, or otherwise strings you along in various ways until you give up). First, my wife and I have played dozens of Big Fish hidden object games for years on a 3rd generation iPad.  We recently got a deal we couldn't pass up on an iPad Pro.  No, I didn't write that to brag.  I wrote that because many of the reviews are commenting about the screen load times.  Well, of course - it's a very new game with big graphics demands.  Look at the download size!  Sure you can complain, but there are hundreds of older Big Fish games for the older devices.  For those of us lucky enough to have newer devices, it's wonderful to have a game that shows what they are capable of.  There is all kinds of extra little animation bits. It's fun to just touch an object to see what will happen.  Okay, not all are relevant to the game story, but it certainly adds to the creepy atmosphere.  We are thrilled that Big Fish took the extra effort to make a game that really takes advantage of 'beefier' hardware.  If you've got it, this game is a must have.
Especially the Bonus game which is almost unplayable in spots.  This ruined it for me.   I have an IPad 2 if that makes a difference.

Hexwar's basic battle system,  but it seems to keep improving with each game. The combat system has a lot of detail, and now you can really look under the hood and see how it all works, maximize your attacks. The flank attack rules are crucially important in this game, and the different types of cavalry mean you really need to know when to shoot and when to charge.   For those unfamiliar with the English Civil War, it took place at a point  between Middle Ages warfare and the age of Napoleon; Cavalry was still quite strong, but not dominant, either charging with the sword or riding up close, firing off pistols and retiring. Armor was being phased out due to the rise of muskets, and infantry would protect themselves with long pike formations, almost like ancient Greek phalanxes, but they also had lots of musketeers attached to blast away at anyone who came close.  At times this system can start to feel a bit generic, as it's been used for everything from World War II to ancient Rome, but this one felt enough like the period to make it work. When I played the battle of Edgehill, there were big cavalry battles on both flanks, and eventually one wing swept around and hit the Parliamentarian infantry in the rear, that felt right.  Compared to Pike and Shot from Slitherine, this one plays a lot faster and is less detailed, but they each have their advantages; Fire and Fury is way less fiddly, and you have a lot more control over your units; Pike and Shot has a lot more chaos, with units retreating like wild or charging when you don't want them to, historically accurate, but perhaps frustrating to some. Another alternative is Musket Smoke, which is also very very good, and no luck factor involved whatsoever. All in all, it's great that there are three games on 17th century warfare on iOS now!   My only request for Hexwar games at this point would be to add some command and rally rules; then again, the current morale system rewards you for retreating your weak units before they get killed. Still, it often feels like units fight to the last man a lot more than they run.  A big improvement here is that they have cut back on the "capture control point and receive reinforcements" mechanic, which really gave a gamey to feel some of the older Hexwar stuff, and it tended to drive the narrative a bit too much. This one is much more like the historical force match -ups, you get what's on the battlefield, and go at it, have to break the other army's line or morale to win. And another big improvement is the really big maps they have now which offer you a lot more ways to go about beating the other army. Well done.  About the only complaint I have with this is that there's no Game Center support. The AI is good enough to make you work for your wins, but I would really love to be playing this against a human opponent!

I have played the majority of kairosoft games and have loved them all. This is the first one I truly don't like. It gives you all the usually kairosoft features which are still present in this game. But the actually gameplay of the matches is flawed. The Cpu player(s) seem to move and play realistically, like they have a goal in mind. On the other hand you will often find your player running around in circles and waiting for no reason to charge up their swing. When playing doubles your players will have no idea what each other is doing and will basically stand right next to each other leaving the rest of the court open as the cpu players spread out and play realistically. Stats aren't a huge factor in this game as you will always be at a disadvantage due to the lack of ai in your own players. Only buy this game if you want to be frustrated and disheartened by losing to players with worse stats and equipment.

I actually had the most fun on the title screen, using the ball to draw lines and play with the ink.

The system is a little confusing because nothing is ever explained to you. What are skill points? How do you get more life points? Skills are learned randomly. Why does a person with 15 def get 1-shot while a person with 13 def takes 1/4 the damage?   But the cardinal sin is that the game has a boring and disjointed story. It reminds me of Chinese movies that recount some popular or historical tale, and you're expected to already know what happens so they can jump around and just hit the highlights.  Just say no. I bought this while on vacation for something to play while in line or on the bus. I won't even be using it for that. $18 down the drain.

I will always have some bias towards Romancing Saga games because of the godly soundtrack by Kenji Ito.   Having played RS1 and RS3, the controls felt familiar; the enemies no longer rush directly towards and trap the player when they enter a map like in the first game (as often), yet the graphics, battle system, and story feel weak compared to RS3. The graphics look cleaner than the original version, and there are now animated boss sprites.   My biggest complaint would be how you control the movement of the main character and overall UI. It's unclear where you should tap when using an item/ sometimes I would press to the side and accidentally consume an item or make a wrong choice. The translations are also... kind of funky. "Seeling skill?" Sealing a skill? What? (Turns out I have to be careful not to tap the skill in the menu twice because that apparently DELETES it?)   Lastly, it's also irritating how you still cannot restore LP at the inn like in RS3, and you essentially have to kill off a character's LP to remove them from your party.   -- TL;DR -- Amazing music, interesting story (but a rather poor execution of it), ugly controls and UI, challenging gameplay.

Saga was one of my favorite series as a kid so I may be a bit biased but I think this remake is really good.    What makes Saga great is the open world and the level of challenge.  The battle system is addictive unique in a lot of ways.    Save often as you can occasionally get into situations where you can't get out of a dungeon or scenario and may not be capable of beating the boss.  Always keep a few different saves going in case you box yourself in.    The game may seem rudimentary and from a story perspective it is fairly simple but the mechanics, challenge and replay value are all really good.  Don't give up after an hour or two.  Play for at least 4-5 hours and I think you will be a fan !

This is the second new game I've played recently from Big Fish that is substantially shorter than their typical hidden object/puzzle adventure game. Unlike the other one (Mystery Tale - In Her Eyes), however, this one at least had considerably more depth. The game showcases many worlds from a wide range of historical eras by cleverly using time travel. There are collectible relics from each era, not too many and relatively easy to find.  There is a balance of HOP and puzzles, ranging from fairly simple to moderately complex; somehow the developer managed to invent new ones, which is always fabulous! Difficulty is configurable to the user, and one can choose match-3 games rather than HOP. The map readily enabled teleportation and indicated live tasks if desired. I could not find a way to easily access the journal without having to go through the map every time, which got frustrating when I had to review puzzle hints; however, this may have been my failure to understand the controls.  I really enjoyed the technology and history in this game, as well as the little surprises built-in when you click on some of the nonessential items; for example, the statue of an archer will shoot an arrow, lava will erupt from the volcano, etc.  Again, however, I can't give this five stars when I finished the entire game and bonus chapter in less than three hours. I hope these short games are not an omen of Big Fish's strategy for future offerings. There is no way I would pay $6.99 for a game this short, and even $3.99 seems like a stretch. I'd rather buy from and support individual developers and get a more robust game.

My rating is closer to 3 1/2 stars, but I'm rounding up because (a) I liked the complex HOPs, (b) the developer went the extra mile with collectibles, and (c) I may be too critical because I personally found the game dull.    The plot never really crystallizes, and the ending to the main game is abrupt.  The bonus chapter is very brief, so it doesn't make up for the shortcomings of the storyline.  However, the graphics, cut scenes and soundtrack are well done, and there is a good blend between HOPs and minigames. Most of the HOPs involve multiple steps, and they are a strong positive for the game.  Also, the developer provided not only a set of collectibles, but souvenirs that you can gather from designated scenes after you have completed the bonus chapter.  The controls need some work. Difficulty is not configurable.  Touch sensitivity for items and movement is erratic.    On the whole, this was a game that I looked forward to finishing, so it's difficult to say that I recommend it.  If you can buy it on sale, you may find it worth your time.

If this app were to add that copy/paste functionality I think the app would be much more successful and allow for increased usability. I had a real sense of accomplishment when I finally completed each game.  The ‚ÄúTimed‚Äù Add-On added another element to an already challenging game.  I had to play it several times in order to successfully finish the game.  Looking forward to future endeavors. All that family honor stuff is obnoxious as hell and taken to an extreme. I found it too stereotypical of Asian culture to be taken to be seriously and couldn't bear to read through all of it. Beyond the ancestral piety bs, not much of a story can be found.

The story was extremely linear. While the choices did change your stats, and the stats affected your choices, there were no "multiple paths" to follow. That was a big disappointment to me.    Another big disappointment was your name... Because you can't change it. And while your family and roommates call you other names "like Cat, or Ghost, or names you have a say in" there is no "input your own name"  There's only one romance as far as I could see. That might be a creative choice on your part, but I think it would have been better to at least have two, so the player can feel like there actually making a choice, rather than forcing this one character on the player. (Not only that, but I wasn't a big fan on the only romanceable character anyways)  In other words, this wasn't my favorite COG game yet. The writing was decent actually, but the lack of actual story-changing choices was a real disappointment.
While the premise and story are interesting, the pressures of conforming to Chinese ettiquette and manners is mentally exhausting. The focus on indirectness also comes off as insincere.

Most of us have had to read one or two of Shakespeare‚Äôs plays in high school. But the problem was that Shakespeare was the last thing we were thinking about. The difficulty of language was a turn off, teachers themselves were not experts in the writing either, so what was the relevance to us? But I think Shakespeare is better appreciated when you have accumulated more personal experience meeting people and delving into some current affairs. I found Shakespeare a more pleasurable experience trying to learn it on my own free time and that is where this app really helps. It has annotations for the entire Tempest play and recorded voice work. So in addition to reading, you get to really ‚Äòlisten‚Äô to the words and the different pronunciations. Through this app, it made me confident to say that although Shakespeare is difficult, it does not mean that it can‚Äôt be fun. If you take the time and take a leap of faith with this app, I promise that you will have a better appreciation of Shakespeare and create an approachable and optimistic view of classic literature.

The artwork and music in this game are breathtaking, as has been notes in many other places. I love many things about the gameplay, such as the well designed and creative abilities and synergies between the heroes. I played through the Mac version of the first game on the computer and I‚Äôm halfway through the second on mobile.  The reason for 4/5 is I keep finding myself wanting certains small changes for conveying information during combat (that wouldn‚Äôt change gameplay at all, but make it easier / more convenient to get all the information about what is happening). Specifically: 1) I mostly use the show all armor / strength display in the top right to get an overview of strong enemies still left on the field. It would be a really helpful thing to do something like add a red outline around the displayed armor / str of enemies to more easily sort through the information at a glance, when there are many units clumped together; currently the display is the same for your own units and enemies, making it quite confusing in the case of many units bunched together. This feels like such an obvious small touch that I‚Äôm surprised it‚Äôs missing given the attention to small details through the whole game as a whole.  2) The biggest lack I feel is the ability to quickly ascertain enemy turn order. In order to figure out the enemy‚Äôs turn order you have to click through each portrait, see where they are on the board, then use the clunky armor / str display to see how much damage the enemies can do etc. If there are more enemies than fit in the queue, tough luck. The game mechanics of this game are very similar to Into the Breach (the biggest difference being the fact that each side gets a turn with all their units in that other game) and I would love to have a button like Into the Breach does for a quick overview of enemy turn orders: when you press it, it shows numbers next to each enemy unit, 1 for the next enemy unit in the queue, 2 for the one after etc  Anyway, great job with the game! Even though I mostly focused on what I wish the game implemented, it‚Äôs still a work of art and wonderful design. It‚Äôs effective at creating a real atmosphere, and the ending of the first game made me cry :*) Perhaps someone has made mods to the pc version with my desired features, Imay have to look into that :)

I had to PAY 5 COINS FOR A MOUSE! A warning would have been appreciated, lol!  Anyway, this was a terrific game. You could customize settings. The graphics were totally magnificent. The game was decently long and had a long bonus chapter. This was my favorite type of game: a fairy tale, twisted as it might be! It was a cross between Rumpelstiltskin and Sleeping Beauty gone wrong. Loading was not quite instantaneous between  locations but the lag time was short. At each location you collect roses and morphing objects. There was no actual journal but objectives were regularly updated. Inventory was labeled and interactive and there were complex items to assemble. There was a marked, if so customized teleport map to transport you. The HO scenes had some variation. Luckily there wasn't an overabundance of them, because you didn't have an alternative. There were many puzzles and games. Some were fun and others were boring rotational stuff that I believe we are all tired of doing. Even so, this game was so gorgeous and fun to play that I didn't care about the puzzles so much.  The gimmick in this game was a wish box which helps you in exchange for drops of blood. It sounds morbid but really is not. It was fun because you learn more of the story and receive help in the game. I deducted a star for the following reasons: lack of a cohesive journal, small lag loading and also for the map to update itself, and too many rotational puzzles. However, all in all it was still an amazing game and I will play it again! It was magical, interesting and exquisite all at the same time. So thanks to all of you for your hard work!

This app/book version of Hawkins famous laymen book is just an amazing piece of learning. You can flip over some topics when you have some time, learn some amazing fact, and come back later which no rush or worry about how fast you are progressing through the book. This tuner worked so well I was considering leaving my other tuners out of my guitar cases.  However, a few months ago, I suddenly found that the tuner was off.  It now registers my 440 tuning fork as about D#.  Apple recently admitted it slowed down older iphones, which they may have done to my iphone (through IOS updates I installed?) and caused the tuner to read about 3/4 what it should. If you are going to load this on an older iphone, perhaps the IOS "updates" will screw it up.

I looked at a dozen tuner apps. It came down to Boss and Fender.  I loaded both and tried them a couple times.  The Fender app didn‚Äôt like the low B string - couldn‚Äôt ‚Äúhear‚Äù it well.  The Boss app performed well with all 6 bass strings!  The chromatic mode locked in quick to each pluck.   I turn my phone on it‚Äôs side and set it directly onto the amplifier face. This displays only the tuning graphics and they are large enough to read from floor level.  When using TU-3W (black) mode my phone remains discrete.   This is the next best option to an in-line tuner!

Ive played the first three games on my Iphone 4S. So that gives you an idea how successful these puzzles are. Each started out on its own before Memento, then they hid Gems in each of the levels (+ series). There‚Äôs also Red Portals that take you to a Secret timekeeper level in Memento.  One of the additions here in ZEN is: One way portal blocks which you come out of the direction the Gold ring sent you.  You can‚Äôt go back through a block however you can move it to a new place you want to send stuff in or teleport out of! The SWEET part lies in certain levels you can actually PUSH the block into the Gold Ring that creates & leads to a WORMHOLE level. Everything move you make there is now REVERSED!   If you never played any of the Quell series before, you can start with the original to see where the game gets better over time. So if you haven‚Äôt got the package of 4 - try Memento first.  The original might drive you a bit MAD as there‚Äôs less variety of puzzles there & more use of closing gates. However, both original & Reflect each have BONUS levels for extreme challenge too.

Dear Fallen Tree Game Makers, I love the Quell games so so much!!! Please consider adding the following updates to all Quell games: ability to reset apps to fresh, erase memory without erasing prior purchases, tips for how to solve/reach very tricky locations for gems and portals whether for purchase or through a link to a blog about the games and how they are designed. I love Quell games so much that I want to go Behind the Quell! I want to know the designers, what inspired their choices, the colors, the music, etc. Thank you so much for making these games for us to enjoy!!!

The Quell series is a significant work of art on all levels. Compelling, comforting, challenging, inspiring.. I would love to have the option to move through chapters at the same level of difficulty as the first level, when I want a purely relaxing experience. As with Memento, I found some of the puzzles too complex to tackle. That said, I'm always looking forward to experiencing more Quell, and I'm grateful that I can turn to these gems that fill my heart.

Dr Panda is definitely a fun game for suitable for children as young as 3 -although some young children may need some assistance unlocking each of the different production areas.   Additionally, the app does offer a game environment which is supportive for a young child conceptual development of certain science and early math frameworks.   However, it is important to note, the "core" of the Dr Panda is that of entertainment and not of education.  This does not mean Dr Panda is not or could not be used in a constructive manner to promote learning.   Indeed, Dr Panda can be used to promote a child early understanding of addition and subtraction facts 0-5; especially when  a parent or other adult plays with the child and encourages he/she to think more deeply with questions/ statements such as: I see you have 2 customers wanting honey, but you can only make 5 jars of honey at a time. How many jars will you have left, after you give 2 jars to your customers.   This type of dialogue between caregiver and child will not only triple the boost to a child's educational skills; it will open the door for the child's understanding in many other cognitive domains.  Final Thoughts: Since gameplay throughout the farm requires precise fine motor skills - most beneficial for young children who are learning to write- I would encourage children to occasionally play this app using a stylus.   As these pre-writers work to twirl the windmill and place eggs in a carton, they will be developing the same muscles needed to write letters and words.

The app requires way too much stability in order to accurately measure between surfaces or points. For example, I tried it in my office, measuring from table top to floor. I got significantly different measurements each time and was told I moved the phone too much. I was simply setting the phone on the floor, picking it up, then setting it on the desk top. Naturally, the phone moved and rotated a bit in the act of picking it up and setting it down. I am not sure I could have been more precise in my movements, but apparently the app requires it.   If I scale this activity up for measuring a building, I would not be able to maintain anywhere near this level of precision and stillness. I do not move like a laser. When measuring a space, I have to walk across a room, or many rooms. I  cannot be expected to not tilt, rotate, or otherwise shift my phone as I move from one point to the next. Often times there are pieces of furniture or other objects in the way.   I think the app requires conditions that are too ideal, and for that reason the measurements cannot be trusted. My work requires very accurate measurements.  I think I‚Äôll stick with my laser. It has not let me down except in sunny outdoor settings.

This is not really a game or a choose your adventure, it‚Äôs a graphic novel where you can make mistakes and have to start over from a checkpoint. I had hoped it was a blend of that and ‚ÄúOut There‚Äù, but it‚Äôs not. It‚Äôs very linear, and there aren‚Äôt really any twists, just false choices. Make the wrong choice? You die, go back to checkpoint. That‚Äôs not ‚Äúdecisions that matter‚Äù that just black and white decisions.  That said, art and music are 5 stars. After 10 you get the addition of the short ladder and fire, at 20 you get the conveyer belt and a bit further you get the ghost on the conveyer belt. ...And that‚Äôs it. There is no more new content (at least that I‚Äôm aware of) after that. That, I think is where the game falls short. After the 30‚Äôs the levels become the same and blend together. I think that this game could very much benefit from adding more to the higher levels. I have bought this game for $3 and I believe it was well worth the price and lived up to expectations fully. However I can‚Äôt feel like there was a lot of potential lost here. The simplicity of this game is what makes it initially love able to play but it gets boring real quick. The way to beat every level is the same. No matter what you‚Äôre up against it takes to brain power to figure out how to properly deal with it, but I must express how empty this game feels with its lack of enemy/unit variety. There are two summonable soldiers and the enemy can use them as well, as far as I can tell your ‚Äúwar tree‚Äù summons the different types randomly. That‚Äôs the one aspect of this game that is appealing and a pleasure to play with. It is for that reason that I take away a star because this game is so simple and yet so much potential is lost because of a lack of variety in anything. New units, perhaps new trees that summon specific units or you choose what your war tree produces when you plant it, would bring this game to life and an open up a new variety of strategies that the player would have to utilize to potentially deal with the new challenges that more unit variety would bring. Given this game is so simple and the A I are direct, it is obvious playing this game adding a new unit would take minimal effort and vastly improve the quality of gameplay and replay ability especially when you factor in the procedural generation this game could easily have.

I‚Äôve been playing this game for almost a year now. It was fun for a while, but slowly became annoying. First of all, I hate how taking your turn costs money. Like, I know it‚Äôs supposed to be a strategy game, but seriously? I mean, are you kidding? I‚Äôve gone bankrupt in 4 turns. AFTER buying. No lie. Make the per turn cost 20 dollars, OR DON‚ÄôT HAVE ONE. Your own earnings are too little, and the small amount you get from the praise and stuff  is pathetic. You spend all of it when it comes to the conspiracies anyway. Second of all, as I said in the title, the decision making results make 0 sense. Say you prevent the mafia from taking over businesses. Why should the common man, opposition, and oligarchies be mad? They are the ones who it affects. This makes the game nigh unplayable. Or why should stricter security screenings make the police and army mad. Occasionally the ups and downs are random. It‚Äôs kind of annoying how no faction can stay neutral. Why should the mafia, army, opposition and oligarchies care if I give the cops more donuts? You have to do what one faction wants, and I get that‚Äôs the point, but make it logical. Why would the police be mad about me cracking down on crime? Why would the police be happy i let the Mafia steal their cars? It‚Äôs so annoying to think you made a good decision, only to find out the faction you wanted to benefit seemed to like something being against them. And the conspiracies are worse. Sometimes you need to pick between two decisions that would be considered conspiracies against you, and the one that costs money is the one that makes the crowd happy. Like what? Me raising an army general‚Äôs salary because he was incompetent makes everyone happy, but firing him doesn‚Äôt? It‚Äôs so stupid, and as I said, YOU DON‚ÄôT HAVE THE MONEY BECAUSE OF THE COST PER TURN. All in all, if the developer made the decisions more logical, and made the cost per turn a LOT less, then I would play it, and love it because the concept is wonderful.

I went over the four apps in my review of the first book, I‚Äôll just add a few things. This is even more complex, tricky and fun than the previous work. Having the rewind feature disabled is a questionable choice. I understand it is frustrating. I would have given the choice to the player, between perhaps a beginner/weakling mode where rewinding is still possible and the full adventure as it is now. Or by giving the player the incentive to give up the rewinding. Or by giving a limited number of rewinds, etc. In the game books, after all, whether the rules forbade it or not, you coud always go back to the previous chapter or to the previous intersection. If you put that reservation aside, the app is again one of the best games out there and the whole series deserves high praise and success.
I agree with another reviewer, make it an option to not have, but don‚Äôt make this great series of games into a frustrating ordeal. Please, please bring the rewind function back for this game!

I have only gripes about this game after attempting to enjoy it several times. 1. There's no real tutorial for piloting the lander. 2. If you fly the lander away from the shuttle, you will‚Äîfor no apparent reason‚Äîreverse course and slam back into the shuttle, destroying the lander. 3. There's a never-ending stream of dialogue that takes up part of the screen that can't be skipped and is too slow to focus on. I tried to read it, but it's not engaging, entertaining, or informative. 4. The gameplay is extremely repetitive and frustratingly difficult, even on the easiest setting. 5. You're always working against a timer, which can build tension if used correctly, but the time limit is too short for new players to get used to the mechanics and have proper time to explore the various objects and enemies found on the asteroids.  Developers, you can still fix this game. Start with 10 minutes on the timer, gradually decreasing that as the player makes progress. Also start with as much of a tutorial for piloting the lander and dealing with the asteroid gravity as the one for controlling the astronaut (the only fun part so far). Let players skip from one message to the next one. Explain some of the pick-ups on the asteroids.  I keep finding this bubble thing, but can't seem to use it for anything. Good luck.

One tried to suspend my account because I disagreed with him on territory policy, and claimed that Uber didn‚Äôt operate in my area.  Funny how I was able to work in my area for the last work week.  Duh!   Now with that being said, I figure that for the first week of my work, with Uber Eats has been really fun and enjoyable; in spite of the issues that just came up.    I am hopeful that a productive resolution will be worked out, as I would not want to be pushed into consideration of going elsewhere.  But we shall see what the outcome will be.

On at couple of levels at least, there are objects that block that camera's view at essential turns that are made often for restarts. This makes it a matter of timing, which is fine, but if the timing is off from the music, holding that timing in your head can get annoying.   To the developer, just go through and find these areas where objects are obscuring the the turns and we'll be golden.  To the consumer, the game is an interesting idea built around the idea that you not only will fall, but you have to sometimes to move forward. Nice little sentiment there, but there are some frustrating aspects (like I mentioned above) that seem more like design flaws than challenges. Can I get past these "flaws" of course, with practice. But I'd rather overcome challenges that feel like their part of the game, not a design oversight.   Give it a whirl while it's free. If not free, maybe browse a bit further to see if another game steals your interest.

This review is middling-to-fair that, while this is more effective than meditation apps for mindfulness, the ads are too distracting sometimes to play.  I'm a perfectionist when it comes to most games. I will restart levels for the smallest of mistakes. Because most games seem to have a taunting set-up, 'this EASY level took you THIRTY tries??'  This game stands calmly and gently opposed to that. Mistakes are welcome, encouraged, and rewarded. The glowing cubes to collect often are along the wrong path. The option of skipping a level is only there as a reminder that, it's okay if you're frustrated, you can try again later.  The level design is exactly how this succeeds in what meditation apps can't for me. There is something unknown out there. You can't see the whole level. You have to engage and explore and, even if you anticipate something, you can easily see how you do or don't "succeed in completing" whatever task you were attempting.  I know that the developers probably can't control exactly what kind of ads they have, but the game would be much better if they didn't flash. It's fair and understandable that they're there, which is why I rated a 4 rather than say a 3. (I was recommended this on an article of pricey but currently free apps. The ads being there surprised me as the app prices tended to be $3-5.)

It only says the names of the fruits once, and that is the first time you play.  My son and I played 7 or 8 rounds of this. We only finished gathering the fruit before Theo stole them on the very first attempt. We planted our 3 seeds, then spent the remaining rounds losing our fruit to Theo. (If you like this, I suggest listening to a song called Tails One). Ash impatiently waited for the right moment. The herd needed to scatter. She slowly walked the perimeter of the prey circle. Ash then sat behind a bush, again, waiting. She dug her claws into the sand. ‚ÄúCome on.‚Äù She whispered. Most of the zebras were asleep, but still others were guarding them. It had to be almost dawn by now. A sudden sound caught Ash‚Äôs attention, and she twitched her ears, hoping to get a clearer sound. Ash looked over to where the giant moon was shining, half of it unseen below the ground. It reflected off of Ash‚Äôs curious eyes as she gasped. Ash saw another wild animal. A silhouette of one anyway. She turned away from the zebras completely. Her stomach rumbled as she took a guilty gaze back at her meal. She hadn‚Äôt eaten in forever though. The silhouette stopped running, and stared straight at Ash. She turned away from it, stalking the zebras once more. Perfect! One of the children had wandered off too far, and everyone (including the child) was asleep. It was too risky to go after an adult right now. Ash zoomed over to it, very gently picking it up. The child didn‚Äôt wake up. Good, she thought. She silently ran to her den with the child in her mouth. The sun began to crest over the Savanna land. The child woke up, drowsily looking up at Ash. It‚Äôs eyes opened wide, and it tried to scream and run, but Ash clamped her jaws around its neck. She bit down. Hard. Immediately, the child went limp. Ash delightfully gobbled it down. She curled up, hoping for some rest. A sudden thought nudged at her. Who was that last night? She squeezed her eye and repositioned, but she sat up, frustrated. A cheetah ran up to her. ‚ÄúFang!‚Äù She shouted, happy to see her brother again. He looked terribly upset. ‚ÄúWhat happened?‚Äù Ash asked, full of concern. ‚ÄúMother is dead.‚Äù He said sadly. Ash let it sink in, then threw herself at the stone wall, causing her shoulder to bleed. ‚ÄúWHAT DID WE DO TO DESERVE THIS!!!?‚Äù She screamed, listening to her echoing cries. A hiss from outside the den sounded. ‚ÄúDid you hear that?‚Äù Fang asked. Ash nodded, not caring at the moment. An alligator walked in, hissing more. Ash gasped. Her and Fang growled back. Pain sliced through Ash‚Äôs leg. She hissed in a breath, looking behind at it. Another alligator snapped its jaws at her and tried to bite her leg again. ‚ÄúFang, there‚Äôs another one!‚Äù Ash exclaimed. Fang attacked the first alligator. In three seconds, Fang was dead. Ash looked with wide eyes for a long time. The alligators tried to kill Ash too, but she raced out of her den, now homeless and alone. She ran out faster than she ever had. Tears blurred her vision repeatedly. The cheetah silhouette walked up to her and Ash tripped, her vision still hazy and blurry. The cheetah looked at her. ‚ÄúYou ok?‚Äù He asked. Ash nodded. ‚ÄúI‚Äôm Blur.‚Äù He said as he helped Ash up. That‚Äôs where it all began. Not long later, they became mates. Ash looked in the distance at her new home, smiling happily at Blur and their cub, who was sleeping in between them. There was a cheetah. One Ash could‚Äôve sworn she saw before. She stood up. ‚ÄúMom?‚Äù She asked in disbelief. Ash raced towards her, feeling exhilarated to run. They almost got to each other when the ground split and shook. ‚ÄúWhat the-? What‚Äôs going on!?‚Äù Ash shouted to Blur. Blur picked up their cub, Dash, and ran over to her. A large gap opened in the earth, and Ash watched her mother and her family hang on to the edge, Dash squealing for help. Ash couldn‚Äôt save anyone. She was frozen. For the first time in the world, Ash‚Äôs fur turned black. She ran over to save them both with her newly found super-speed...  The world turned black. Ash saw nothing but darkness. It was confusing, then she saw why. Ash was not supposed to exist. Now that her existence had become irrelevant, the world had to swallow her up, starting with her family. That‚Äôs why Fang died. That‚Äôs why she was going to die. Her superpowers made sure of that. Wait- her superpowers!!! Ash ran and ran and ran until her paws hurt. She was running up the earth, but she didn‚Äôt know if she had time to save anyone this time. She almost made it to the top, and the earth closed up on her, just like that. She was moving so fast, though, that she was simply phasing through the earth. Ash would soon fall into space. She closed her eyes. Though her life seemed to be speeding by in her memories, she took everything for granted. Ash opened her eyes, and she was on the ground. What just happened? Ash looked around. It was the Savanna. Blur walked up to her. ‚ÄúAsh!‚Äù He said excitedly, ‚ÄúWe can time travel!‚Äù  TO BE CONTINUED.

Thanx for the heads-up, Izzyoc (and Dracyy) and for telling us about upcoming games. I just wanted to let everybody know that I really handed BigFish their heads on a platter, for the whole Puppet Show debacle. I accepted NO EXCUSES and NO GENERALIZED ANSWERS! I threatened them, basically. So Puppet Show is no longer available. For those of you who bought it, ERS is working to fix it and then will bring it out when it is working properly. They tried and brought out another version but it did not fix the problem, and obviously BigFish doesn't seem to be on their case to fix it! So don't worry about it for now! On to Phantasmat. I was concerned about playing it because the subject matter (murdering family and using their remains, such as bones and ashes, in their artistic endeavors) is truly gruesome and macabre! This game is not for children! When I played it, it was such a fantastic game that I felt the same way as both Dracyy and Izzyoc. The storyline held my interest. There are 3 difficulty settings, although there is no option to customize the settings. It was a decently long game and had a bonus adventure. The graphics were eerily gorgeous and very crisp and clear. The cut-scenes were chilling and quite frightening! At each location you collect a rocking horse and at some you collect a morphing object, and there is an indicator which tells you when you have them. The morphing collectibles allow you to access portfolios of the Ward family. There were many locations and loading WAS instantaneous (for a change) between locations! There is an in-game marked (dependent on settings) teleport map to use. You learn the story via notes, and objectives were regularly updated. Inventory is labeled and interactive and there are complex items to assemble. The HO scenes had variation, and if you preferred not to play the scene you could play match-3 instead. I actually enjoyed the puzzles in this game; there were some new ones and they weren't only boring rotational junk! My actual rating is 4.5 stars, and I deducted half a star due to lack of a cohesive journal. The game ran smoothly and I did not encounter any glitches. This game was extremely clever and I enjoyed it immensely. I even bravely fed the mouse and thought that it was kind of cute (EIPIX did not torture me too much!) Of course I will deny EVER saying a mouse was cute, lol! Lynxie sends lots of ‚ù§Ô∏èüíãüòò to the intrepid, fabulous and hard-working Dream Team Elite! Keep up the great work, and please also keep pestering BigFish to get Puppet Show updated. The more we annoy them, the more pressure they will have to do it! I cannot do it alone, although I really have tried! Please Dracyy, KimTwilight, Izzyoc, Opinion, Sunshine Susie, Deana M and Catalina, keep sending nasty emails to BigFish. A lot of people bought the game and it is unplayable! What will it take for ERS to finally update it?

Good game. It reminds me of NiGHTS, and Yoshi's Island. Nice idea, cool gameplay. Challenging but fun. My biggest gripes are the abundance of ads, and the child. Let me explain. This game is like Yoshi's island in that if you're damaged, a "child" that is riding you gets thrown off, with a ten second timer to retrieve it. This would be fine, if the child was not constantly thrown ABOVE the screen, where you can't reach it. Once you go above-screen, however, it will throw you downwards, meaning you have even less of a chance. Another issue, though less pronounced, is that your power up will deactivate and immediately leave you exposed to the enemies were about to run into. At least there could be a few safety frames before being fed to the dogs?  Edit: Controls really aren't a problem. Hold the screen, you spin in one direction. Let go, spin in the other. Tap over and over, you'll go straight. It's simple unless you have such a bad sense of timing that you overshoot where you need to go. I have had very little problem with controls.  TL;DR, Many little glitches woven into a good idea. This if a complicated recommend, but if you're interested in playing the game, knock yourself out.

This game is an undersea challenge in which you control your jellyfish character through dangerous caverns to reach keys that unlock higher levels, while collecting gems along the way. The game has potential to be an enjoyable little title, but has several issues hindering its success.  First, the intro to the game is a non-interactive animation.  You're visually shown what to do in the game, where instead you should be prompted to try the controls, and get a feel for the gameplay.  Once the animation is done, you're thrown into the first level with tap left/right instructions, and left to explore the level.  Normally, this type of introduction could work, but the one-life/start-over gameplay leads to frustration.  The level design suffers from what has been described in other reviews: the beginning stages are particularly difficult, taking numerous attempts to complete what should be simple, easy goals to build player confidence.  After your character (repeatedly) braves spiky walls to reach the level goal, you're presented with a key contained in smooth-looking semicircular ring, which you might expect to be a haven after all the effort required to reach that point.  But no, touch any part of the ring and it's start over (again).  It could make sense to add this level of difficulty at higher levels and introduce an additional challenge, but including this behavior in the first levels is a recipe for game deletion for all but the most dedicated players.  Enabling the character to take up three hits before having to start over would at least allow some planning to complete the level.  In terms of style, the game sports well-designed visuals, and the cute jellyfish character responds with the appropriate physics behavior.  The dubstep soundtrack isn't bad, but seems out of place given the undersea setting and the floating, undulating movement of your jellyfish.  Speaking of the character, you will unlock different jellyfish as you progress, but it's not clear whether the characters have any significantly different abilities, or are just style upgrades.  As it stands, Slip Away Mystify is fairly daunting out the gate and will likely appeal only to those seeking high difficulty challenges. Hopefully the developers can rethink the gameplay and level progression, but in its current state, it's difficult to recommend.

Flud presents challenging puzzles with polished design and animation. Its grid-clearing concept bears some similarities with games like Mr. Square, Fold, and Blip Blup, but features its own unique mechanics.   The puzzles are well-crafted and satisfying to solve, striking a good balance between logical deduction and lateral thinking. The animations provide some nice eye-candy, but they're just slow enough to become an annoyance during play, as the UI stays completely unresponsive until after all the blocks have finished doing their dance. This means waiting several seconds every time you make or undo a move, which quickly grows tiresome as the levels become difficult.   The tiny navigation buttons can be hard to press on smaller devices. I've experienced occasional minor glitches, both with the graphics and placing arrows, but nothing that critically hindered play. The app does seem to use more CPU than necessary, battery drain has been an issue on my device.   However, all of these faults are overshadowed by the quality of the puzzles. Overall, Flud is a fun, challenging puzzler that could benefit from a few under-the-hood refinements to improve the user experience.

I played (and continue to play) Siralim 1 and had a blast with it; one of the things I really appreciated was that it's one of the few in-depth games my old iPad can run without any problems. Needless to say I was psyched about this game, especially because it looks like they fleshed out the spellcasting system a lot (creatures can cast spells now with indvidual stats, and you don't have to worry about running out of charges on your best scroll and having to search for more scrolls once that happens) and made character class have more of an impact-- not to mention the various quirky gods (the god of anger who always cusses at you might be my favorite so far, though it's a close call between him and the creepy/flirty spider goddess of poison). However, one problem: the game has a very annoying tendency to crash when someone (either me or my opponent) casts a spell in combat. I'm still giving it 3 stars because it looks like they tried to take some measures to fix it, with options letting the game run more smoothly on lower-quality devices, and it's nice that they're showing consideration for players like me who don't have the newest devices; also, it seems like it would be a lot of fun if it didn't do that every time. Maybe add an option kind of like Turbo Mode but that only disables spell graphics or something, not all combat information? I don't know. Looking forward to playing this when they get the bugs ironed out.

Hi, Izzyoc! I wish I had seen your review but today our XFinity was down for 5 hours so TV was out of the question! I have nothing else new to play so I guess for the price I'll try it. By the way, do you have any idea when some of the games you listed will be released for iPad? I can't wait for a new Expedition; it's one of my favorites. Thank you so much for all of your input! I actually liked this game a lot more than I thought! First of all, you could customize the settings. Orneon actually gives us a journal, a feature sorely lacking by other developers. The game was lengthy, with a bonus adventure. The storyline wasn't overly complicated, or even really unusual. Still I liked it because I had no trouble following it. Objectives were regularly updated.The graphics were incredibly colorful and gorgeous, and the cut-scenes were electrifying, especially when you use the magic lamp and enter the time portal. Loading was instantaneous between locations and and there was a marked, if so customized, teleport map to transport you. There was no map in the bonus adventure, but I don't know why that was the case. Inventory was labeled and interactive. There was a lot to do at each location. You also had a neat device to use to dispel evil magic. Collectibles included flowers and morphing objects. The HO scenes had variation and some were more like puzzles. The puzzles/mini-games were diverse: there was some boring rotational stuff, some games of skill, some coding puzzles, but at least there were many puzzles and there was something for everyone. I was very happy not to deal with any major rodents! Thank you, Dracyy! I deducted a star for the following reasons: I found that some of the puzzles were very hard to manipulate, although the game ran smoothly otherwise. I didn't like the hint system because it was a spoiler. Lastly, with such magnificent graphics, we were not given any gorgeous wallpapers in the extras section, and I would have loved them! This was still a good game and I would definitely enjoy another sequel. I would like to say Happy Thanksgiving to the entire DTE and the other gamers/reviewers as well! For the first few levels, I thought this was a great game, totally worth the $.99 in app purchase to get rid of ads. But then, the developer made several typical mistakes that made me drastically lower my rating and eventually delete the game.  First after maybe 20 minutes of easy levels suddenly becomes impossible. It could get much too hard, and playing the same level, over and over and over and over and over and over and over again it‚Äôs tedious, not fun. And then it gets even worse, as even if you played over and over that many times they‚Äôre just not solvable. Soon I discovered why this was‚Ä¶  I tried tapping on the next level, since there was a level that I clearly was never going to get past even if I replayed it over and over and over and over and over and over and over again 1 million times, and I was told I had to watch three videos to get to play the next level. Well, having paid money for the game, I object to having to watch videos, especially several of them in a row, but in this case I said OK.  Well, here the developer got greedy, because I watched a video after video after video, way more than 3, and it wouldn‚Äôt ever let me play that next level. After watching seven videos I gave up and deleted the app. Giving 2 stars instead of one because I did have about 15 minutes of fun playing it. Too bad the developer blew it... this could‚Äôve been really great, five star game.

I cannot tell you how many times I‚Äôve played this game, and then have my phone die because of the game. (I personally think it‚Äôs because of the background. If I don‚Äôt understand what is being explained, I either read it over or simply look at the choices and see which stat the choices utilizes best. There was a game in 2011 called Tetra3D that I used to play all the time. It was the same as Tetris, wherein you could move the block anywhere on the board by turning the board one turn (as you can with this game) but you could also move the placement of the block (in Kubik, if a block is going to land in the middle, no matter how you rotate it, it will land on the middle of whatever side it ends up on). Further in Tetra3D you could rotate the block along the x, y, and z axes.   The game stopped working a long time ago and hasn‚Äôt been updated in years, in fact I can no longer find it in the App Store. Kubik is the closest game I have found to my former favorite game, but as it is now missing the ability to move the blocks as freely as I expect has made the game frustrating and not fun.   If possible I would love more ability to rotate and flip blocks, and to move the location of the falling blocks rather than just being able to rotate the base that they are falling onto.   Thanks!
